<HEADLINE> BMW Threat to Close Rover Longbridge Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) - BMW, the owner of Rover, is
considering closing the Longbridge plant in Birmingham, unless
workers there consider a radical reform of their working
practices.
</P>
<P>
The blunt warning came from Bernd Pischetsrieder, chairman of
BMW, the German carmaker which acquired Rover in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the British International Motor Show in Birmingham
Tuesday, Pischetsrieder said a sweeping review of Rover's cost
structure was under way.
</P>
<P>
"Options under investigation include further job cuts, the
reduction of employment costs and increased working flexibility,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder complained that there was a 30 percent
productivity gap between Longbridge and BMW's German plants,
mainly because of exchange rates and pay levels.
</P>
<P>
He ordered an all-out drive to bridge the productivity gap,
saying that "short term actions are required for the long-term
future for Rover Group".
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder confirmed that he had briefed British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, and the Secretary for Trade and Industry,
Peter Mandelson, on the plight of the Longbridge plant and was
seeking a response by the end of November.
</P>
<P>
His statement overshadowed what should have been Rover's big
day at the Motor Show, with the launch of its first all-new model
for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair gave his backing at the same day to BMW's
efforts to make the company profitable, hoping that the new 75
model would be a "world-beater". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
