<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Faces Food Crisis: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho is facing
shortage of food with more than 35,000 children living in
communities going hungry unless they are supplied with food soon,
a United Nations official said in Maseru Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho Department of Education has appealed to the U.N.
for emergency food supplies for the most vulnerable children,
South African Press Association quoted U.N. official Peter Lassig
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lassig, representative of the U.N. World Food Program (WFP),
said that food aid cover was requested to cover a period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
The WFP said earlier it would mobilize international donors to
alleviate Lesotho's food woes which were resulted from political
crisis in the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties claimed since August that the May
23 general election was rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho
Congress for Democracy. In mid-September, social unrest and
political turmoil, including looting and arson, occurred in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the military intervention by South Africa and
Botswana, the situation in Lesotho has stabilized.
</P>
<P>
Last week France said it would provide Lesotho with emergency
food aid worth 300,000 Francs (about 56,000 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
