<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Schroeder Agree on Moscow Summit in Mid-November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and German chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder on Wednesday agreed
to meet in Moscow on November 16-17, the presidential press
service said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a telephone conversation
between the two, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, Yeltsin and Schroeder discussed a
number of issues concerning bilateral cooperation and interaction
with international financial organizations, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin
denied reports that Yeltsin's health was worsening.
</P>
<P>
"This is absolutely wrong," Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Yeltsin had had a planned medical examination
at Moscow's Central Clinical Hospital earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest bout of rumors surrounding Yeltsin's health came
after his visit to central Asia earlier this month, when a cold
and subsequent bronchitis forced him to cut short his trip to
Kazakhstan by one day.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin suffered two heart attacks in 1996 in the wake of the
June 16 presidential election. He also had quintuple heart bypass
surgery in November that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
