<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Central Bank Predicts Downward Rate Move in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
has indicated that countries adopting the single European currency
euro is set to reduce their interest rates to a level similar to
that of Germany ahead of the euro debut in January.
</P>
<P>
Eugenio Domingo Solans, a member of the ECB director board,
said Tuesday evening that Germany's current short-term rate of 3.3
percent has been viewed as the target for the required convergence
of interest rates in the euro zone ahead of the euro launch.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the international club of economic journalists in
Frankfurt, Solans also noted that it was up to the national
central banks of the countries adopting the euro to decide whether
to make a one-time big cut or rather to take a gradual approach to
bring their interest rates to a same low level until the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The current average lending rate across the 11 countries in the
euro zone is about 3.8 percent, with a gap of up to three
percentage points between the highest and lowest rates.
</P>
<P>
With the ECB now indicating at a downward rate convergence,
money traders in Frankfurt said that they did not expect the
German central bank, the Bundesbank, to still cut the country's
interest rates as the U.S. Federal Reserve did recently.
</P>
<P>
Germany's incoming government to be formed by the Social
Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens has been calling for a rate
cut in order to spur economic growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer, however, said recently
that the interest rate convergence in the euro zone would be
equivalent to a rate reduction for the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Solans on Tuesday also said that the ECB will adopt a
stability-oriented monetary policy similar as that of the German
Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
To defend price stability, the ECB would monitor the amount of
money supply combined with a secret inflation target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
