<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Set up for Nigerian Railway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has set
up a ministerial team to ensure timely completion of the railway
rehabilitation project undertaken by China Civil Engineering
Construction Company (CCECC).
</P>
<P>
The 3,505-kilometer railway rehabilitation project which was
scheduled to be completed last September was delayed due to the
unavailability of the track materials including steel rails,
fittings, screws and turnout.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian paper said Wednesday that the Nigerian government
was uncomfortable with the delay which was believed to be caused
by senior ministry officials who have allegedly politicized the
project.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that while the Nigerian Finance Ministry
wanted the supply contract awarded to competent firms, senior
officials in Transport Ministry had allegedly frustrated such
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Transport Minister Rear Admiral Festus Porbeni put
the blame in the execution of the project on Nigerian contractors
who he stated failed to perform when he visited Lagos last month.
</P>
<P>
Porbeni said that he had ordered the contractors to perform or
get their contracts revoked, adding that he had given an October
ending deadline to supply materials.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Nigerian capital Abuja told the paper that the
government decided to set up the team to ensure that the right
materials are bought for the rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that members of the team had traveled with the
contractors to Vienna in Austria for the purpose of evaluating
the materials being purchased.
</P>
<P>
CCECC Deputy General Manager Chen Xiaoxing was quoted as
saying that "at the moment, we are almost doing nothing because
the materials are not available."
</P>
<P>
Chen added that the firm's job has almost ground to a halt
over the non-availability of the track materials.
</P>
<P>
The contract for the rehabilitation of the railway lines which
in the last two decades has witnessed tremendous decadence was
signed in December 1995 at a cost of 528 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The contract profile includes reduction of gradient covering a
distance of 80 kilometers, elimination of curves covering a total
of 380 kilometers, and maintenance of tracks by reballasting,
leveling and tampering to cover 3,233 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The contract also covers the rehabilitation of 50 locomotives,
150 coaches, 400 wagons, 100 guard vans, design and survey works,
and man-power training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
