<HEADLINE> Museveni Elaborates Stance on Congo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- President Yoweri Museveni
elaborated Uganda's stance on the crisis in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) Wednesday, defending its military
presence in the eastern part of Africa's third largest state.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the State House Nakasero here
Wednesday evening, Museveni said Ugandan troops are deployed in
eastern Congo (K) because of the uncertainty of the situation
there.
</P>
<P>
They are mainly to defend the national interests from there
where rebels fighting the Ugandan government have bases, said the
Ugandan president.
</P>
<P>
The deployments are a precautionary measure the country has
taken so far, he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the Ugandan army there is involved in fighting
in the war-torn country, Museveni said that they are not involved
in major fightings there.
</P>
<P>
The president said he had advised Congolese President Laurent
Kabila to have a wide political base in his country, but the
latter turned a deaf ear to his suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Building a cadre is very important to a country, he noted, and
the armed uprising againore troops there than two battalions as reported by
some newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government does not have plans to send
reinforcements there, Museveni said, adding that Uganda will pull
out its troops as soon as the region works out a lasting solution
to the conflict in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused of backing the rebellion in the DRC
since its eruption on August 2, but Museveni denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 8,000 foreign troops including
Zimbabweans, Angolans, Chadians and Namibians are fighting
alongside Kabila's forces.
</P>
<P>
Museveni had just exchanged views with Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa Sunday before
going on to Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day working visit to South Africa, Museveni
held day-long confidential talks with his South African
counterpart Nelson Mandela on how to remove the Congo crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
