<HEADLINE> IMF, Russia Start Talks on Delayed Payment of Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 21 (Xinhua) -- An International Monetary Fund
mission and ranking officials from Russia's key economic
ministries started talks here Wednesday on the next tranche of IMF
loans.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda in the talks between the IMF mission and
officials of Russia's Finance Ministry, the Economics Ministry and
the State Tax Service would be an overdue payment of 4.3 billion
U.S. dollars out of the Fund's bailout package, originally
scheduled for September, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
IMF experts would study Russia's budgets for the fourth quarter
of this year and for next year, Interfax quoted a source close to
the talks as saying.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to discuss with the Russian officials
structural reforms concerning the social sphere, monopolies in
natural resources and reform of the country's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
As the IMF sees it inevitable that the Russian central bank
would print "a certain amount" of money to finance the budget
directly, the IMF would now try to keep down the amount of money
printed, Interfax quoted a Russian expert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russian Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said Tuesday that the
government will not print more than 20 billion rubles in the
fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission is expected to stay in Moscow until the middle
of next week. On Thursday the IMF experts will meet with Russian
First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Later Wednesday, Zadornov told the local Ekho Moskvy radio that
Moscow expects to receive part of the 4.3 billion dollar tranche
from the IMF before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
"This is obvious, as time has run out," Zadornov said, noting
that Russia would have to 17.5 billion dollars on its foreign
debts next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
