<HEADLINE> Israeli University Students Protest Against High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli university students
held demonstrations in the major cities on Wednesday to protest
against high tuition fees, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
In the coastal city of Tel Aviv, the students blocked a highway
and also scuffled with police. Thirty-one demonstrators were
arrested during the clash.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, police dispelled a group of demonstrating
students to keep the major roads from being blocked. No clash was
reported.
</P>
<P>
The students are demanding that tuition fees, currently about
9,500 shekels (about 2,200 U.S. dollars) a year, be reduced by
half.
</P>
<P>
They also threatened to launch a nation-wide school boycott on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Finance Ministry has turned down the demand, noting
that the tuition level was set by a joint commission established
after a student strike in 1996, which also included student
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Education Minister Yitzhak Levy is scheduled
to meet students' leaders later on Wednesday in an effort to forge
an agreement to prevent the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
