<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Link to Georgian Mutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Vadim Gustov on Wednesday denied allegations that Moscow
was behind Monday's military rebellion in western Georgia.
</P>
<P>
"It's a search for nonexistent enemies," Gustov said of the
allegations by some Georgian politicians. "Why should Russia need
this? Russia has a lot of problems of its own."
</P>
<P>
Georgian officials, including President Eduard Shevardnadze,
have said Russia might have played a role in the rebellion, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Gustov, on a visit to Vladimir, a city 176 kilometers southeast
of Moscow, said he plans to visit Georgia soon.
</P>
<P>
"We must live like good neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Early Monday morning about 200 Georgian servicemen led by Akaki
Eliava, a supporter of former President Zviad Gamsakhurdia, took
10-13 tanks and armored vehicles from the Senaki motorized
infantry brigade in an anti-government mutiny.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday, most of the rebels, and the seized tanks and
armored vehicles, have returned to the Senaki base and the Defense
Ministry regained full control over the the Senaki motorized
infantry brigade, although Eliava and and some supporters remain
hiding in the forests.
</P>
<P>
One government soldier was killed and two others wounded in the
mutiny. 
</P>
</TEXT>
