<HEADLINE> Regional Summit on Congo Crisis Held in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Regional leaders held a
one-day summit in Harare Wednesday to discuss the crisis in
Democratic Congo, a report of the Pan-African News Agency (PANA)
from the Zibabwean capital said.
</P>
<P>
Embattled Congolese President Laurent Kabila did not appear at
the meeting which is attended by Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos, Namibian President Sam Nujoma and Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe, said PANA.
</P>
<P>
But Kabila has sent his senior minister Victor Mpoyo to
represent him, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Mpoyo was quoted as saying at the Harare International Airport
upon arriving that he is representing Kabila because the
president is not feeling well.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the summit disclosed that Angolan President
Dos Santos had pressed for the meeting after the Tutsi-led rebels
took over the strategic town of Kindu in east Congo (K) recently.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe have deployed troops in Congo to
help President Kabila crush the rebellion which started in early
August.
</P>
<P>
The summit came ahead of a high-level meeting of ministers of
defense and foreign affairs of the 14-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC) scheduled to take place in Zambian
capital Lusaka next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to bring the two-month-old Congo
crisis a step closer to a peaceful solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
