<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks Full Implementation of U.N. Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi stated here on Wednesday that Iran seeks full
implementation of the U.N. Security Council resolution and that
of a regional meeting on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the remark in a meeting with visiting
U.N. Secretary General's special envoy for Afghan affairs Lakhdar
Brahimi, who arrived here on Tuesday on the mission to defuse the
tension between Iran and the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran has done its utmost for the realization of the
international community's resolve and "we hope that the current
trend will lead to the desired results."
</P>
<P>
Following the tension between Iran and the Taliban triggered
by the killing of nine Iranian diplomats and reporter in
Afghanistan in August, the U.N. Security Council passed the
resolution 1193, condemning the killing of Iranian diplomats and
urging to stop genocide in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from six neighbors of Afghanistan as well as
Russia and the United States also held a so-called "6+2" meeting
on Afghanistan in New York last month. The meeting called for
U.N. efforts to defuse the tension between Iran and Afghanistan
and to investigate the killing of Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stressed that the Taliban leadership shoulders the
responsibility to identify and punish the killers of the
Iranian diplomats and reporter. He also called for immediate
release of all Iranians still kept by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister thanked Brahimi for his efforts in
helping release 26 Iranian hostages, who returned home last week
after the U.N. envoy visited Kandahar, the Taliban's headquarters
in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban has so far set free 51 Iranians, but it was not
clear how many Iranians are still in their captivity.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi briefed Iranian foreign minister of his recent
negotiations with officials of Pakistan and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
He said the international body's resolve is to make the
Taliban accept the international community's demands. 
</P>
