<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece to Conduct Joint War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A joint search and rescue
operation by Cyprus' National Guard and Greek Armed Forces will be
conducted on Friday as part of Cyprus' on-going military exercises.
</P>
<P>
An official statement said here Wednesday that the operation to
be held some 30 nautical miles west of the western coastal town of
Paphos will be participated by the Greek Air Force and Navy units
as well as Cyprus' Search and Rescue Center, the air and navy
rescue units of the National Guard, the police and the Port Police.
</P>
<P>
The operation is aimed at training the forces involved in
real-life conditions within the Nicosia Flight Information
Region, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus began Tuesday the six-day military exercises, code-named
"Nikiforos '98," with the participation of the Greek Armed Forces
amid tensions on this Eastern Mediterranean island following the
Cypriot government's decision to buy Russian-made S-300
anti-aircraft missiles last year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has warned that it will strike the missiles if they are
deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that at the same time, one frigate, one
destroyer, a submarine and two torpedo boats of the Greek Navy
will dock at Limassol and Larnaca ports on south and southeast
coast of the island. The warships will be open to the public over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The military exercises will be concluded with a parade of
the participating units in Larnaca on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Greece and Cyprus signed a joint defense
pact in November 1993, under which Greece will provide Cyprus with
air, sea and land cover in case of a fresh Turkish offensive
against Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to protect
the Turkish Cypriots, who declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," recognized only
by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
