<HEADLINE> Uganda's Economy Running Well: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni said here Wednesday that Uganda's economy is running
well and it is growing at a very high rate.
</P>
<P>
Commented on the economy at a press conference Wednesday
evening, the president said road conditions in Uganda's
infrastructure have improved because 39 of the 45 districts have
road maintenance units.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the weakening Ugandan Shilling against the
U.S. Dollar, Museveni said that this is maybe due to the fact
there are fewer Dollars in the market.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the depreciation of Shilling against the
Dollar is somewhat good to Uganda's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Strong Shilling is more dangerous to the economy than the
weak Shilling. Weak Shilling is not bad for the economy at all.
It encourages exports and discourages imports," the president
said confidently.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Ugandan Shilling is in a free fall against the
Dollar. The exchange rate dropped from 1,200 Shillings to one
Dollar to the present 1,350 to one and it continues falling.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts here attribute the depreciation to the shrinking
coffee exports and the volatile situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Many investors have withdrawn their money out of the country
because of Ugnada's alleged involvement in the 11-week-long
conflict in the neighboring Democratic Republic of Congo. 
</P>
