Savimbi of the opposition National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) on September 12, urging the UNITA to implement
the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process has fallen into stalemate because
the UNITA refused to demilitarize all of its troops and surrender
major areas formerly controlled by it into the hands of the
government.
</P>
<P>
In September, the Angolan government changed its stance,
cutting off links with the UNITA led by Savimbi. It declared that
it only recognizes the breakaway UNITA Renovation Committee as
the sole legal dialogist in the peace process, thus bringing the
United Nations mediation to a halt.
</P>
<P>
The widening crisis in the Great Lates region was also on top
of the talks between the Angolan army chief and the U.S.
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy said the international community is concerned
over the tension in southern Africa, hoping that the warring
sides can sit down at the table to negotiate for a peaceful end
to the conflicts. 
