<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Marine Corps General
Anthony Zinni, the commander of U.S. forces in the Gulf, Wednesday
criticized a plan approved by the U.S. Congress to help Iraqi
opposition topple President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Noting that he saw no unified, viable opposition to Saddam in
Iraq, Zinni warned that Saddam's abrupt overthrow under such
conditions could split Iraq and destabilize the region.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think these questions have been thought through or
answered. If they have, no one's asked me about it," he told a
group of reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be honest with you, I don't see the parts that make it
sensible," he said. "I think a weakened, fragmented, chaotic Iraq
-- which could happen if this isn't done carefully -- is more
dangerous in the long run than a contained Saddam is now."
</P>
<P>
Last week, U.S. Congress voted to permit the Clinton
administration to spend 97 million U.S. dollars on military aid
for opposition groups in Iraq with the goal of removing him from
power.
</P>
<P>
The non-binding "Iraq Liberation Act of 1998" does not require
the administration to change the U.S. policy of containment of
Iraq. It also allows two million U.S. dollars in funding to
opposition groups for radio and television broadcasts into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The danger here is that I don't see a lot of viability in the
opposition groups. I see the potential for Kurds going one way,
Shiites going another way, the center going some way," he said.
</P>
<P>
The general worried that the U.S. move could create internal
turmoil in there that could lead to an Afghanistan-like situation
in the end. 
</P>
