</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of Iranians, Khamenei said that the
people's massive turnout in the election would "carry a special
weight in disappointing the enemies of the Islamic Republic" of
Iran, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that "over the past year, the enemies have been trying
to discourage people's active presence at the polls so as to make
the Experts Assembly an institution without popular support."
</P>
<P>
A suitable reaction for the nation is to turn out in huge
numbers at the polls, which will also be a display of national
maturity and dynamism, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the election atmosphere prevailing in the country, the
Iranian leader said that beyond any doubts, the people, by their
huge turnout at the Experts Assembly polls, would inject a new life
into the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian constitution, the 86-seat Experts
Assembly is responsible for determining the country's supreme
leader and to review his performances. It also has the right to
dismiss the leader if he fails to carry out his duties.
</P>
<P>
Some left-wing factions have gradually cooled on the election
of the Experts Assembly after some of their prominent candidates
were rejected by the conservative-dominated Guardians Council,
which is empowered to screen the qualifications of candidates for
elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
A number of left-wing candidates also withdrew from the
election campaigns in a protest to the Guardians Council's
screening policy, while several leading left-wing groups refused
to announce their lists of candidates. 
