<HEADLINE> IMF Expresses Welcome for U.S. New Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said Wednesday a decision by U.S. Congress to approve
17.9 billion U.S. dollars in new financing for the institution is
"essential and most welcome."
</P>
<P>
Shailendra Anjaria, the IMF Director of External Relations,
said in a statement that the other 181 IMF members are now voting
to ratify an increase in funding quotas that will flow from the
release of funds by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. contribution will help increase IMF resources by 90
billion dollars when other nations make their shares.
</P>
<P>
"The scene is now set for the full ratification of the IMF's
quota increase by the membership and for the IMF to continue to
transform itself in a way that ensures its continuing relevance to
the... globalized world economy," Anjaria said.
</P>
<P>
As for some conditions attached by the U.S. Congress, the IMF
is "still studying the details," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Initial impressions and reports suggest that many of the
ideas, particularly in the areas of greater transparency of the
IMF and the terms of IMF lending, are in accord with the broad
directions being taken by the IMF membership," Anjaria said.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF's executive board will now consider ways the
"reforms will be implemented" and how "to further improve the
effectiveness of the IMF."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the U.S. conditions on the IMF financing would also
limit the length of certain loans, require higher interest rates
and open the often-secretive organization to more public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Approval by at least 85 percent of the membership is required,
with the U.S. holding 17 percent of all voting rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
