<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Trying to Restore Charges against Clinton's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr suggested Wednesday he is still investigating Webster
Hubbell for obstruction of justice as he asked a federal appeals
court to revive tax-evasion charges against the former
presidential confidant.
</P>
<P>
Starr told the court a judge erred earlier this year when he
dismissed the tax charges against Hubbell, his wife, accountant
and tax lawyer. The judge ruled that the prosecutor had exceeded
his authority in bringing the charges.
</P>
<P>
Starr had been investigating whether more than 700,000 dollars
in payments Hubbell received from President Bill Clinton's
supporters in 1994 was designed to buy his silence in the
Whitewater investigation. Instead, Hubbell was charged with
failing to pay taxes on some of that money.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell, who resigned the No. 3 Justice Department job in 1994
and later pleaded guilty to defrauding the Arkansas law firm where
he and Mrs. Clinton worked, quietly observed Wednesday's arguments
from a seat in the courtroom. His wife, Suzy, an Interior
Department employee, sat next to him.
</P>
<P>
When Judge David Tatel asked why Hubbell was charged with tax
violations and not obstruction, Starr suggested the latter issue
remained under investigation.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the court should indulge the presumption there
is no evidence of obstruction," Starr said. He then offered to
secretly show the judges some of the grand jury evidence regarding
obstruction.
</P>
<P>
That drew an immediate objection from the defense lawyers.
Attorney Chris Todd, who represents Hubbell's accountant, told the
appeals court that "to put in this case the specter (of an)
ongoing obstruction investigation" would be unfair.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell's lawyer, John Nields, reiterated his arguments that
the prosecution of client was too far from Starr's original
mandate to prosecute Hubbell on charges of bilking his law firm
and clients.
</P>
<P>
Making his appeal, Starr argued in court documents that the
money Hubbell received from Clinton supporters may be related to
his "noncooperation with respect to Whitewater and Madison-related
matters."
</P>
<P>
Whitewater was the Clintons' Arkansas real estate investment
with Jim and Susan McDougal, the owners of the failed Madison
Guaranty Savings &AMP; Loan that was the original focus of Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge James Robertson ruled on July 1 that Starr
should have gotten Attorney General Janet Reno's approval before
prosecuting Hubbell. In addition, he ruled that the prosecutor's
use of Hubbell's financial records violated the defendant's Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
Starr "investigated Mr. Hubbell's fees to determine whether
they were paid to influence his testimony," Hubbell's lawyers said
in court papers. "Finding nothing," the attorneys wrote, the
prosecutor "embarked on a tax investigation straying far beyond
those fees."
</P>
<P>
Starr did not charge Hubbell with obstruction, but rather
brought a 10-count conspiracy indictment alleging an attempt to
"evade and defeat the payment of a large part of the income tax
due" by the Hubbells in 1989-1992 and 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department said Starr should have gone to Reno to
seek an expansion of Starr's investigation. The department opposed
Hubbell on the Fifth Amendment issue, saying Starr was entitled to
use Hubbell's financial papers to prosecute him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Work of UN Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The functions and role
of the United Nations Security Council should be strengthened,
China stressed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the session of the General Assembly on the the
work of the Security Council, Chinese Deputy Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Shen Guofang said the
Security Council shoulders major responsibility for the
maintainance of world peace and security in accordance with the
Charter of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Shen said as an important organ of the United Nations, the
Security Council should listen to the views of the vast number of
member states so that its actions would truly reflect the will of
the entire membership of the Organization.
</P>
<P>
Shen said practices over the past year had shown that the
leading role of the Security Council in maintaining world peace
and security was irreplaceable, and it should follow strictly the
stipulations of the Charter and act upon the will of the majority
of member states in carry out its duties so as to retain its
authority.  
</P>
</TEXT>
