<HEADLINE> UNICEF Has Not Suspended Operation in DRC, Statement Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to an earlier
published news report, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
on Wednesday issued a statement here, saying it is continuing its
relief operations in rebel-held areas of the Democratic Republic
of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"UNICEF has not suspended operations in any area of DRC," the
statement said, "However, it is true that operations in rebel-held
eastern DRC have been severely hampered as a result of widespread
looting and pilferage."
</P>
<P>
"Over 1 million U.S. dollars in transport and communications
equipment have been lost, in additional to medical supplies,
educational equipment and food for children that had been stored
in UNICEF warehouses," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
These losses, combined with lack of staff security and
humanitarian access to people in need, obviously limit efforts by
UNICEF's local staff to go about their vital work, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNICEF programs continue normally in other areas of
the central African country, the statement said, "They are focused
on meeting the health, nutrition, water, sanitation and
educational needs of children and women."
</P>
<P>
In Bascongo, in the southwestern part of the country, 135
health workers have been refurbished and restocked with essential
drugs and medicines thanks to a recent agreement between UNICEF
and the Government of the DRC, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF, a development agency working in the country for many
years, began its presence since the outbreak of conflicts in the
eastern part of the country, said an official, reached on the
telephone by Xinhua.  
</P>
</TEXT>
