<HEADLINE> S. Africans Sentenced in Angola for Aiding Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Three South Africans have
been sentenced to 23-year jail terms in an Angolan court for
flying missions in support of UNITA rebels, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted sources as saying that the three, Charter Flight
Company owner Johnny Parreira, pilot Peter Bitzker and flight
engineer Mark Geoffries, were not in court Tuesday to hear their
sentences.
</P>
<P>
Co-pilot Antoine Sterrenberg, who is a foreign national with
South African resident status, also received a 23-year sentence
in absentia.
</P>
<P>
The men were arrested with four other South Africans in
January when their aircraft was intercepted by the Angolan Air
Force over Menongue in southeastern Angola.
</P>
<P>
The group included construction workers Rudi Swanepoel and
Willem Steyn, pilot Marnix van der Eecken and Martin Steyn, whose
occupation was not known. The two Steyns are brothers.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, the men apparently departed from South Africa
and landed at Jamba, the venue of a former National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) base.
</P>
<P>
They left shortly afterward and were on their way to either
Andulu or Bailundu, headquarters of UNITA, when they were
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
The eight men were taken to a Luanda prison. After about a
month, Bitzker, Geoffries and Sterrenberg were released and
charges against them were withdrawn. Angolan authorities
apparently later claimed they escaped, and the case was
re-opened.
</P>
<P>
The remaining five men were taken to a Menongue jail about
four months after their arrest, from where Parreira managed to
escape about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel and Willem Steyn were sentenced to two years in prison,
while van der Eecken and Martin Steyn received 10-year prison terms.
</P>
<P>
Parreira's wife claimed her husband had not made contact with
her since his escape. The whereabouts of Bitzker, Geoffries and
Sterrenberg were also not known.
</P>
<P>
No extradition treaty exists between South Africa and Angola.
</P>
</TEXT>
