<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tries to Save Mideast Summit Out of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Wednesday that it expected to give new proposals to Israel and
Palestine Wednesday despite an Israeli threat to walk out of the
Middle East summit in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
"We hope and expect during the course of the day to be able to
provide a text of what we will think will help the two sides reach
the agreements necessary to put the peace process back on track so
that we can advance the security and situation of both peoples,"
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"That hasn't happened yet, but we expect to be able to share
such a text with both sides during the course of the day," said
Rubin at the Wye Plantation, which is 110 km east from Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to provide all the assistance, the creativity
and the persuasive powers that we can but we can't make decisions
for them. We are not holding people here against their will," said
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't call it a treaty. It's a text designed to put the
current business and the old business of the interim agreement
into effect so that we can move on to the permanent status talks,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. President Bill Clinton is returning to the
talks for the sixth time.
</P>
<P>
Rubin at first declined to be drawn on the Israeli threat to
pull out but later said the U.S. mediators had been asked what
preparations would be needed before departure.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have information at this time that any of the
relevant parties are leaving. I mean, there are logistical
issues," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Israeli delegation threatened to walk
out of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the U.S. mediators had retreated from previous
understandings, the Palestinians were avoiding clear commitments,
a senior Israeli official said, "There is a serious crisis. The
Israeli delegation is threatening to leave."
</P>
<P>
Aviv Bushinsky, spokesman for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, also suddenly talked tough about the Wye Plantation
negotiations. "The Palestinians are acting in a zigzag."
</P>
<P>
"Without a specific guarantee to change the (Palestine
National) Charter... there can be no agreement. And likewise with
the extradition of terrorists," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinian side said they and the Israelis had
moved closer to a deal on land and security, reaching agreement on
many details of a complicated package.
</P>
<P>
In response to Israel's threat to withdraw from the talks, a
senior Palestinian official said it would not be in the interests
of Israel to leave the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We have no information of any crisis. If they want to leave
now, it would look bad for them and we are not in trouble," the
Palestinian official said.
</P>
<P>
The United States had no immediate comment but a spokesman for
Clinton, who has spent five of the last six days nursing the talks
along, earlier dismissed media reports that full agreement was
imminent.
</P>
<P>
"I would dissuade you from the sense that there is some deal on
the table," said spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Reports had said that some progress had been achieved in the
talks Tuesday and leaders were expected to sign an agreement
Thursday at the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
