<HEADLINE> Syria Confirms Deal With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Syria has confirmed its
promise made to Turkey not to let an outlawed Kurdish party
operate on its territory.
</P>
<P>
The promise was contained in a deal signed with Turkey Tuesday,
the official Arab News Agency reported on Wednesday in the first
official confirmation of the deal.
</P>
<P>
The deal has apparently defused the weeks-long tension between
the two countries. Turkey has accused Syria of supporting the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK). Damascus denied the charge
while Ankara unleased a threat of war.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day bilateral talks held in Turkey's southern
province of Adana, the Syrians termed the PKK, which is fighting
for independence in southeast Turkey, as an outlawed party, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Syrian officials told their Turkish counterparts that the PKK
is not allowed to operate in Syria or launch actions against
Turkey's security from its territories.
</P>
<P>
But the Syrian side denied there is any PKK military bases or
camps in Syria as claimed by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on setting up a joint mechanism to
exchange information via a hot-line between the security officials
of both countries and their respective embassies.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said the meeting was held in a satisfactorily
positive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was initiated by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
in his capacity as the chairman of the last Arab summit and
Iranian President Mohammed Khatami in his capacity as the chairman
of Organization of Islamic Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
