<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Drops in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation rate
dropped slightly to 0.7 percent in September, its lowest since
last December, Statistics Canada said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The last time a lower annual price increase was recorded was in
May 1962, except the period between February 1994 and January 1995
when the increases were artificially low due to tobacco tax
reduction.
</P>
<P>
Canada's annual price increase has slowed since this Summer,
the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The tiny increase in September was due primarily to higher
fresh fruit prices and hotel rates.
</P>
<P>
But Lower gasoline and computer prices, as well as lower
electricity rates offset those increases, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
