<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inter-party Talks Back on Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's main political parties
have worked out an agenda here Wednesday for a meeting to be
attended by party presidents, signaling the start of the
inter-party talks.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing after the meeting, Michae Sata, co-chairmen
of the inter-party talks and national secretary of the ruling
Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD), said the meeting will
be held within a month and the ruling party proposed the summit
be chaired by MMD President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Nontheless, Sata said political parties are free to meet for
consultations and decide who will chair the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairmen Mainza Chona of the opposition United National
Independence Party (UNIP) said at the briefing that Wednesday's
meeting to amend the agenda went on smoothly and there were free
discussion among leaders of political parties.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairmen Guy Scott of Lima party said he is happy at
Wednesday's meeting and it is encouraging to see some top MMD and
government officials at the meeting, which indicated the
government is serious with the inter-party talks.
</P>
<P>
Scott expressed his hope that the ruling party will continue
with the political dialog.
</P>
<P>
Early last December, 31 political parties worked out an agenda
at preliminary meetings for the inter-party dialog.
</P>
<P>
However, as the party leaders were preparing to participate in
the dialog, UNIP leader and former president Kenneth Kaunda was
arrested for alleged involvement in the October 28 failed coup.
</P>
<P>
In protest against Kaunda's arrest, many parties announced
their withdrawal from the planned dialog.
</P>
<P>
After his release from under house arrest early last June,
Kaunda called for the resumption of the inter-party dialog.
