<HEADLINE> Second Mobile Phone Operator Launched in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Mobile Telephones Network
(MTN), a South African company, came into operation here
Wednesday and became the second national mobile operator in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The coming of MTN ushered in a new era of telecommunications
in Uganda along with Celtel, a British company which came here in
1993.
</P>
<P>
To attract potential subscribers, the newcomer offers much
lower service charge, lower monthly subscription, wider coverage
and better service.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of their business, hundreds of people
thronged the company to apply for mobile service.
</P>
<P>
Allen Muller, the subscriber operations manager, said they
have so much business for the first day that all the staff have
to be engaged.
</P>
<P>
Having more than 90,000 lines open to customers, MTN now has
network coverage extending from greater Kampala through to
Entebbe (45 kms south of Kampala), Jinja (80 kms east of the
capital) and the eastern district of Iganga, to be immediately
followed by coverage in Bombo and Mpigi surrounding the capital.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, its service will further extend to
more distant districts of the country. Their roll-out strategy is
aimed to cover all major towns and cities and many rural areas in
the country within five years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the Ugandan government has been carrying out an
ambitious reform program of public enterprises. In the
telecommunications sector, two key aspects of reform were used:
privatization and competition.
</P>
<P>
In August 1997, Parliament passed the Uganda Communications
Act which provides the legal framework for the introduction of
competition in the telecommunications sector and later the
privatization of Uganda Telecom Limited.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, the Privatization Unit organized a two-day
Investors Forum. Later, MTN beat all the other four bidders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
