<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Palestinians, Israelis to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said on Wednesday that it
hopes the Palestinians and Israelis will reach an acceptable and
balanced agreement at their ongoing summit in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with his Cypriot
counterpart Ioannis Kasoulides, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said his country supports the efforts exerted by the two
sides in a bid to strike a West Bank accord.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by U.S. President Bill Clinton, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu have
been holding intensive talks since last Thursday in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
They are reportedly moving closer to overcoming differences
over a U.S. proposal demanding Israeli withdrawal from 13 percent
of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian crackdown on Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab countries to sign a peace treaty with
the Jewish state in March 1979.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kasoulides expressed confidence that any progress
in the peace process would reflect favorably on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said his country backs all efforts to find a
settlement between the Palestinians and Israelis, hoping their
current talks would yield positive results.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Egypt and Cyprus signed an agreement on
encouraging and protecting investment and avoiding double taxation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will pave the way for more cemented bilateral
economic cooperation, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also praised Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
efforts to defuse the recent Turkish-Syrian tensions.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of supporting Kurdish rebels seeking
independence in southeastern Turkey and recently massed troops
along its border with Syria, sparking fears of a regional armed
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The tensions have been eased as shuttle diplomacy of Egypt and
some other countries helped Ankara and Damascus reach an agreement
Tuesday under which Syria, admitting Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party a terrorism organization, promises to ban the group
on its territories.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot foreign minister arrived here Tuesday for a
three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
