<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henney Confirmed as FDA Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- New Mexico cancer specialist
Dr. Jane Henney was confirmed Wednesday as the first woman
commissioner of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voice vote to approve Henney came a day after
Senator Don Nickles, a Republican and Senate Majority Whip, said
he supported the nomination. Nickles had delayed final action to
dramatize his dislike of past FDA policies.
</P>
<P>
Henney succeeds Dr. David Kessler, who clashed with some
Republicans over his aggressive efforts to stem underage smoking.
Kessler left the post last year to become dean of the Yale
University Medical School.
</P>
<P>
Henney, 51, nominated in June to replace Kessler is vice
president of the University of New Mexico's Health Sciences
Center. She served as Kessler's deputy from 1992 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
The FDA regulates drugs, medical devices, foods and cosmetics
that make up 25 percent of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said in a statement, "The nation now has
an FDA commissioner who is committed to assuring that Americans
have safe food, safe and effective drugs and medical devices and
improved public health."
</P>
<P>
Nickles, in a Tuesday speech on the Senate floor, announced the
lifting of his opposition because he said he had assurances from
Henney and Health and Human Services (HHS) Secretary Donna Shalala
that the FDA and HHS would not take advocacy positions on
contentious issues such as tobacco and abortion.
</P>
<P>
A 1973 graduate of Indiana University's medical school, she was
a senior investigator at the National Cancer Institute (NCI) by
1977. She went on to become the NCI's deputy director and, in the
late 1980s, was running the University of Kansas medical school.
</P>
<P>
At New Mexico, Henney supervises a medical school, college of
pharmacy and several teaching hospitals. She also is president of
the United States Pharmacopoeia, a nonprofit group that sets drug
purity and quality standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
