<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Reaches 22 in Texas Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The death toll has risen to
22 Wednesday as flooding across central and southern Texas has
worsened since torrential rains over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
As 60 counties, one-fourth of the state, were flooded, Governor
George W. Bush Wednesday asked President Bill Clinton to declare
20 of the counties disaster areas, freeing up access to aid.
</P>
<P>
Scattered light rain and drizzle were expected across much of
Texas Wednesday amid speculation that the cost of the damage could
reach 400 million U.S. dollars. In Comal County alone, officials
estimated 266 million dollars in home losses and another 27
million dollars for businesses.
</P>
<P>
In Wilson County, along the San Antonio River, homes sustained
an estimated 140 million dollars in damage, with another 7.5
million dollars to public infrastructure. Other counties were
still compiling dollar estimates.
</P>
<P>
Victoria, 160 kilometers south of San Antonio, met the worst
flooding in 60 years. Up to 600 homes had water damage and about
100 people were staying in five shelters.
</P>
<P>
In Cuero, 40 miles to the northwest and upstream,
three-quarters of the town was under water. The Guadalupe River
crested at nearly 15 meters, well over its six-meter flood stage.
At least 2,000 people in the community of 7,000 were homeless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
