<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Economy Growing at High Rate: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni said Wednesday evening at a press conference that the
national economy is running well and is growing at a very high
rate.
</P>
<P>
As for infrastructure in the country, the president said road
conditions in the country have improved because 39 of the 45
districts have road maintenance units.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the weakening Ugandan Shilling against U.S.
Dollar, Museveni said this is maybe due to the fact there are
fewer Dollars in the market.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the depreciation of Shilling against the
Dollar is somewhat good to the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Strong Shilling is more dangerous to the economy than the
weak Shilling. Weak Shilling is not bad for the economy at all.
It encourages exports and discourages imports," he said
confidently.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Shilling is in a free fall against the Dollar
recently. The exchange rate has dropped from 1200 Shillings to
the present 1350 Shillings to the Dollar and the downfall is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts attribute the depreciation to the shrinking
coffee exports and the volatile situation in the region. Many
investors have withdrawn money from Uganda because of its alleged
involvement in the 11-week-long conflict in Congo (K). 
</P>
</TEXT>
