<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Turnout Expected for S. Africa's General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- About 81 percent of South
Africa's eligible voters are likely to vote in the 1999 general
election, according to a survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The expected turnout is still high, but is 10 percent lower
than the 1994 election turnout.
</P>
<P>
The MarkData survey found that of the 2,230 respondents
polled, 61 percent were certain they would cast their votes,
while 22 percent said they would probably vote.
</P>
<P>
Ten percent were uncertain and four percent gave a thumbs down
to the election.
</P>
<P>
The reasons given by those who said they would not vote ranged
from inconvenience to predictability, dissatisfaction, fear of
unrest and lack of proper identity documents.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that 91 percent of African National
Congress supporters were likely to cast their ballots, compared
with 67,79 and 82 percent of Pan Africanist Congress, National
Party and Democratic Party supporters respectively.
</P>
<P>
About 74 percent of Inkatha Freedom Party and 93 percent of
the Freedom Front supporters would cast their votes, while 86
percent of United Democratic Movement's supporters would vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
