<HEADLINE> S. Leonean President Ends Visit to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah left Nigerian capital Abuja Wednesday after a
two-day official visit to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly before his departure for home, Kabbah
expressed his gratitude to Nigeria over its effort to ensure
peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
He said he came to Nigeria to brief General Abdulsalam
Abubakar over the activities of Nigerian military men in his
country, where a sub-regional peacekeeping force led by Nigeria
is fighting a guerrilla war against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
During their talks in Abuja, the two leaders discussed issues
of common interest, especially security in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah's visit is believed to be part of the ongoing efforts
in preparation for the forthcoming summit of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) slated for October
30-31 in the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
In a similar mission, Chadian Minister of Mines, Energy and
Petroleum, Abdoulaye Lamana met Abubakar in Abuja
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the presidency said Lamana brought a
special message from President Idriss Deby to the Nigerian
leader.
</P>
<P>
Lamana told Abubakar of his country's difficulties in
procring petroleum products for power generation and requested
for assistance from Nigeria, which is Africa's top oil producer
but is also suffering from acute fuel shortage due to ailing
refineries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
