<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Suspends Indonesia's Visa-Free Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government
has suspended Indonesia's visa-free status to block hundreds of
asylum-seekers from the country.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) Thursday quoted
Immigration Minister Tuariki John Delamere as saying that New
Zealand Government's suspension of Indonesia's visa-free status is
based on the fact that his country has seen a "dramatic increase
in the number of Indonesians seeking asylum in the past six
months."
</P>
<P>
The visa-free system had been set up to encourage tourism, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Delamere noted that the rise in asylum seekers from Indonesia
coincides with deepening economic turmoil in the country.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that more than 300 refugee applications have been
received in the past four months from Indonesian nationals who
have traveled to New Zealand on three-month visitor permits and
then claimed refugee status.
</P>
<P>
"By suspending the visa-free status for Indonesian nationals we
are better placed to manage the risk of people seeking refugee
status once they arrive here," he said.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Immigration Minister announced that an
immigration office would be opened in Jakarta to manage visa
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The Television New Zealand Thursday quoted Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Don McKinnon as saying that the visa-free status
is not permanent and the suspension has nothing to do with the
violation of human rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
