<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Receive 273m Dollars WB Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will receive the
largest ever credit worth 273 million U.S. dollars from the World
Bank (WB) for its road rehabilitation maintenance project, an
English daily newspaper here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement in this regard between the Bangladeshi government
and the International Development Association (IDA), the WB's soft
lending agency, was signed here Wednesday, The New Nation said.
</P>
<P>
"This largest credit from the World Bank, which is also the
largest credit for Bangladesh to receive from any agency, will
help Bangladesh to build and maintain 1,800 kilometers of roads
throughout the country," WB country director in Bangladesh Pierre
landell-Mills said after signing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The IDA credit is provided at a concessional rate of 0.75
percent which is repayable in over 40 years with a grace period of
10 years.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is estimated at 528.5 million U.S.
dollars, of which IDA will provide 273 million dollars and the
Department for International Development of Britain will provide
22.8 million dollars and the Bangladeshi government 232.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will further expand and upgrade its most-traveled
roads and bridges, improve highway safety, and revamp its Roads
and Highways Department to make it more efficient with the help of
this IDA credit.
</P>
<P>
The project funds will also be allocated to help repair roads
that were damaged in this year's devastating floods as part of the
World Bank's broad post-flood assistance program.
</P>
<P>
The Roads and Highways Department under the Ministry of
Communications will be responsible for implementing the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
