<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Oil Companies Report Losses in Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Big U.S. oil companies
Wednesday reported a steep decline in their third-quarter earnings
and attributed it to the lowest oil prices since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles-based Occidental, whose third-quarter net income
fell over 75 percent to 38 million dollars from 157 Million the
same period last year, was the worst losser. Its avenues fell to
1.7 billion dollars from last year's 2.0 billion dollars in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Texaco Inc.'s third-quarter earnings fell by more than 56
percent to 215 million dollars from last year's 490 million
dollars, with its revenues dropping to 7.71 billion dollars from
11.09 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Income of the Amoco Corp. fell 49 percent to 295 million
dollars from 635 million dollars last year, with its revenues
dropping to 7.5 million dollars from almost 9.0 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The nation's biggest oil company Exxon Corp. also reported its
profits tumbled 23 percent down to the lowest in four years, with
a net income of 1.4 billion dollars, down from 1.82 billion
dollars in the same period last year. The company's revenue slid
to 28.8 billion dollars from 32.75 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
All the big oil companies attributed their lower earnings to a
slump in crude oil and natural gas prices and continued economic
instability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the average quarterly crude oil prices
were at the lowest since 1986, and natural gas prices fell 11
percent from a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
