<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics Show Hungarian Economy in Sound Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Statistics of macroeconomic
index show that the Hungarian economy developed well this year,
said the National Bank President Suranyi Gyorgy on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation rate of this year may drop to 12
percent from 18.4 percent last year, two percentage points lower
than the 14 percent target. This figure may drop further to 9
percent by the end of 1999, Suranyi said at a meeting of the
National Commission of Budget.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) increased by about 5.1 percent
in the first half of 1998 and exports grew by 20 percent in the
same period, Suranyi said.
</P>
<P>
As the growth of imports is slower than that of exports, the
foreign trade deficit is estimated to be 2.5 percent of the year's
GDP, and the budget deficit may account for 4.4 to 4.6 percent of
the GDP, both lower than the planned targets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Suranyi also said that the foreign currency reserve of the
country reached 8 billion dollars. It can offset the indirect
impact of the Russian economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
