<HEADLINE> hke102221 -Benefits of Reforms Yet to Reach Indian Consumers: CII </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Despite the deregulation and
privatization of infrastructure industries, benefits of better
service quality and lower costs are really not visible in the
sector, Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a paper "Report on Issues Facing India's Infrastructure
Development," CII said that in certain sectors like power, radio
paging and cellular telecom where the output is highly marketable,
private sector interest has been high. But in segments like urban
infrastructure, where services like water supply, sewerage are
seen as public goods with little or no direct user charges being
levied being the norm among customers, the "progress has been
limited."
</P>
<P>
The CII report paper has also put forward some proposals for
development of the country's infrastructure in the fields of
power, telecom, building of ports, airports as well as industrial
parks. Private sector should be encouraged to participate in
infrastructure projects, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
