<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Hikes Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian parliament on
Wednesday approved a bill raising the country's poverty line and
the minimum wage considerably to mitigate the adverse effects of
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the Ukrainians' monthly poverty line will be
hiked 60 percent to 119 hryvna (33 U.S. dollars) starting from
October 1 this year, and the minimum wage will be nearly tripled
to 148 hryvna (41 dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to labor officials, the government will have to add 8
million hryvna (2.2 million dollars) to the budget this year to
cover these new spendings.
</P>
<P>
Compared with early this year, the hryvna has depreciated about
75 percent against the U.S. dollar after the financial crisis hit
the country this August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
