<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Poland, Czech Republic to Renew Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic Wednesday called for
resuming cooperation among the Visegrad Group.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after their meeting here, Hungarian
Prime Minister Orban Viktor and his Polish and Czech counterparts
Jerzy Buzek and Milos Zeman decided to meet every six months to
discuss cooperation, which started in 1991 but stopped afterwards,
among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, the prime ministers reaffirmed their
responsibility for maintaining traditional European values of
democracy and safeguarding human rights.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the three countries had made great
progress in joining the security, political and economic systems
of the West.
</P>
<P>
The three countries will join the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) before its summit in April next year, they
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
They said they are also very optimistic about their talks on
joining the European Union, pledging to continue their cooperation
in various areas.
</P>
<P>
On February 15, 1991, presidents or prime ministers of Hungary,
Poland and Czechoslovakia met in Hungary's Visegrad and decided to
coordinate their efforts to establish multi-party parliamentary
systems in their own countries, exchange experiences on switching
to the market economy and joining the European Community.
</P>
<P>
The three countries were later referred as the Visegrad
Group. After the breakup of Czechoslovakia, the group also
included the Slovak Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
