<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Hurt in Refugee-Police Clash in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 100 people, including 11
policemen, were injured on Wednesday in a clash between police and
Rohingya refugees at a refugee camp in southeastern Bangladesh's
Cox's Bazar district.
</P>
<P>
The incident began at about 1 p.m. when a group of refugees at
the Nayapara refugee camp attacked the policemen who were trying
to stop a clash between two rival refugee groups, press reports
here said Thursday, quoting police sources.
</P>
<P>
The clash between the two rival groups took place when some
refugees of one group went to rescue one of their fellowmen from
the clutches of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
The refugees fired rubber bullets and hurled brick-bats at the
police, injuring 11 of them. Some 100 Rohingya refugees were also
injured, most of them were women and children.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested 33 refugees from the camp and took control of
it.
</P>
<P>
They also recovered an official vehicle of the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), which the refugees took
possession in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
To fend off further trouble, four police teams have been
deployed in the camp, housing 12,712 refugees.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250,000 Rohingyas crossed Bangladesh border in 1991,
and about 230,000 of them have been repatriated under the joint
supervision of the Bangladeshi and the Myanmar governments and the
UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
Repatriation of the refugees to Myanmar has been suspended
since July 1997 reportedly as result of the refugees' refusal to
return, and to date about 21,000 Rohingya refugees are still
staying in two camps in Cox's Bazar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
