<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Missions Abroad Ordered to Meet Their Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
directed the missions abroad to fulfill their respective export
targets to meet the urgent requirement for post-flood
reconstruction, a source of Foreign Minister told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A special directive has been sent to the embassies, high
commissions and consular offices to gear up the export campaign,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
The export target for the current fiscal year (July 1998-June
1999) had been set at 5.85 billion U.S. dollars, and of this, the
target for the embassy in the United States is 2.23 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The embassy in the U.S. is looking after 10 countries -- the
U.S., Mexico, Guatemala, Colombia, Nicaragua, Guyana, Peru, Chile,
Bahama and Venezuela, and Bangladesh exported goods worth 1.93
billion to these countries during the last fiscal year, exceeding
the target by 20.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is followed by the embassies in Germany and France where the
export targets have been set at 595 million and 490 million
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The export target for the high commission in Britain has been
set at 481 million dollars while for Rome at 311 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's export to the Central Asian countries of
Uzbekistan, Kirgizstan and Kazakhstan rose significantly, and the
export to the three countries were set at 0.34 million in the
1997-98 fiscal year, but actual export rose to 2.29 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
