<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Military Seeks ICRC Intervention to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's military has sought
the intervention of the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) to end the wave of abductions of children engineered by the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), according to military
sources Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The military has also sought ICRC assistance to obtain the
release of children already abducted by the LTTE, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The abductions take place mostly in areas unpatroled by
government troops. Most of the abductions are in areas controlled
by the LTTE at some places in the Batticalao District of the
Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has stepped up its conscription campaign following a
depletion of its ranks with heavy casualties in recent battles
with the government forces in the North of the country, the
sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE told a United Nations representative in May this year
that it will not recruit children in its war with the government's
armed forces. This promise was given to a senior UN representative
who visited the uncleared Wanni in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, police believed that over 3,000 fresh fighters from
among children were recruited recently by the LTTE rebels who have
been fighting a 15-year war against the government for a separate
Tamil state in the north and east of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
