<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Lifts Threat to Quit Mideast Peace Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu on Wednesday night withdrew his threat to quit
the Middle East peace summit as the Clinton administration
scrambled to keep the talks going.
</P>
<P>
"Israel wishes to achieve an agreement and hopes there is a
similar desire on the Palestinians' side," Netanyahu said in a
statement after a lengthy meeting with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton followed the developments from the
White House as U.S. and Israeli officials worked on revising the
security provisions that would be part of any land-for-peace
swap. Presidential spokesman Lockhart said Clinton's schedule
Thursday was open for possibly returning to the talks.
</P>
<P>
"These are serious and difficult issues that we're still
working on," Lockhart said, "What we need -- and hope we'll see --
are serious efforts to make progress on these issues."
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians said they would reject any new Israel
demand.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a statement from Netanyahu's office said, "The Israeli
government has packed its bags, including the prime minister.
Take off is scheduled for 10 p.m. (0200 GMT)."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and key U.S.
administration officials have been staying in the Wye Plantation,
Maryland, for seven whole days to break the 19-month deadlock in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier statement on Wednesday evening, Israel side
identified the two stumbling blocks as the Palestinian Charter,
which contains several anti-Israel provisions, and whether
terrorist suspects would be extradited to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel asked Palestine to convene a session of Palestine
National Council, or the Parliament, whose 700 members live in
exile, to remove anti-Israel provisions in the charter. Palestine
insists it is unnecessary since the provisions were canceled in
1996 and only need the approval of the Executive Committee.
</P>
<P>
Israel further demands that the Palestinians extradite 30
Palestinians accused of killing Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
