<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archaeologist Discover Ashes of Early Buddhist Monks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered 10 pieces of bone ash of eminent Buddhist monks in
a bronze coffin in the Fawang Tower in Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The light grey to slightly yellow relics, or Sariras in
Sanskrit, were wrapped in silk in a 4.6-cm-tall glazed bottle.
</P>
<P>
The bronze coffin was in a newly discovered underground chamber
of Fawang Tower in Zhouzhi County, about 80 kilometers from the
provincial capital of Xi'an. The 30-meter-tall tower was built in
601 by Yang Jian, an emperor of the Sui Dynasty (581-618 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
Han Wei, the head of the Shaanxi Institute of Archaeology, said
that according to history, Yang Jian received 31 of these relics
from a nun named Zhi Xian.
</P>
<P>
In 601 he issued an imperial edict to build a tower to house
the bone ashes and to have them put in it at precisely 12:00
o'clock on October 15 the same year.
</P>
<P>
Han said that these are the first relics of eminent Buddhist
monks from the Sui Dynasty archaeologists have found and that they
will do further research on the mystery surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
The relics were discovered when the local government decided to
move the tower 2.8 kilometers away to make way for a water
project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
