<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke102213 -Registration of Myanmar Refugees at Thai Border Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has began registration this week
of the Myanmar refugees in Thai border camps under a mutual
agreement which will see the U.N. agency playing a greater role in
overseeing the camps, The Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The week-long work of UNHCR and Thai Interior Ministry
officials commenced on Monday at the camps in Tak and Mae Hong Son
provinces, Northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was endorsed by Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai earlier this year, heralds a change in the long-time
policy of the Thai authorities who have still now kept foreign
agencies from observing the Myanmar camps.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand decided to permit the UNHCR to step in mainly
because Thailand has been hit hard by the economic crisis, making
it difficult to single-handedly look after the 100,000 Myanmar
refugees in 12 camps along the border.
</P>
<P>
The camps were set up for Myanmar people who fled inland
fighting. The UNHCR will set up an office in each province where
camps are located, and mobile units will oversee them.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the UNHCR will be provided with free and
early access to the camps, contrary to the past when they were not
permitted to work there. Previously, they had to notify the camp
authorities in advance if they wanted to travel to the camps, a
well-informed source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR will provide money for constructing buildings and
procuring the items necessary to administer the camps.
</P>
<P>
But, the UNHCR and the Thai authorities have not yet reached a
conclusion on the money to be provided, the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
