<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Private Aircraft Manufacturer (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China's first and only private
aircraft maker, the Beijing Keyuan Light Aircraft Industrial Co.,
Ltd., started with a dream and was founded on a shoestring.
</P>
<P>
Its 42-year-old founder, Yuan Yongmin, a native of Beijing,
explains that it was the reforms and opening up that helped him
realize his my dream.
</P>
<P>
The dream started early. "When other kids were collecting
badges with the portrait of Mao Zedong, I was busy making model
planes," he recalls, and made the models out of paper, earth, or
wood, whatever materials were at hand.
</P>
<P>
After he finished middle school, Yuan was sent for two years as
a "re-educated youth" to a village. In 1978, he was assigned to
work as a pastry cook at a state-run food company, making 19.08
yuan a month. But, he kept his childhood dream alive, spending all
his spare time making more models, this time out of metal and with
tiny motors that could fly a few meters high.
</P>
<P>
But, he kept asking himself, "When can I ever afford to build
a real aircraft?" The chance came in 1986, when Beijing began
auctioning off some small, money-losing state firms at the start
of its enterprise reforms.
</P>
<P>
So Yuan, whom his wife calls an adventurer, left the food
company and bought a snack bar with 140,000 yuan in loans from
relatives and a local bank. The small business turned out to be a
success and soon allowed him to open a larger restaurant in the
downtown area that now brings him more than a million yuan in
profits a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Private Aircraft Manufacturer (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1992, he found out that a university in Nanjing, the capital
of Jiangsu Province, had developed a multipurpose light aircraft,
the AD-200, and decided that it was high time for him to combine
his hobby with his career.
</P>
<P>
With his wife's backing, he mortgaged the restaurant for about
20 million yuan to buy the patent and 8 hectares of land to build
his aircraft manufacturing company.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Yuan got a license from the Civil Aviation
Administration of China, and this simple move marked the end of
the decades-old state monoply of China's civil aviation
industry. That company can now employs more than 50 people and can
make 500 light planes a year.
</P>
<P>
Its AD-200 has a top speed of 150 km per hour and a maximum
altitude of 3,000 m. and is used for aerial spraying, patrolling,
and sport flying.
</P>
<P>
His company is the only manufacturer of this kind of aircraft
outside the United States, says Yuan, confident of the viability
of his products, which sells for 250,000 yuan (30,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The restaurateur even sees a similarity between his two
completely different businesses. Both of them demand knowhow and
good timing, he explains, but admits that aircraft do not exactly
sell like cakes. In the company's first two years, not a single
plane sold.
</P>
<P>
This year, things have taken a turn for the better after he
launched a promotion drive and orders have come in from and
inquiries from as far away as Saudi Arabia, Canada, and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The company has sold 6 AD-200s to date and another 20 are on
order and Keyuan is even branching out into hot-air balloons.
</P>
<P>
Yuan is looking at a 70 percent share of the domestic market
and a footing in the international market and says that flying a
private plane could be a hobby for the new rich in the new century.
</P>
<P>
And, he's now trying to groom his 15-year-old son as a
successor, while preparing to open a private air sports
club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
