<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seizes Over 2,000 Kg of Drugs in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities seized a
total of 2,143 kilograms (kg) of narcotic drugs, including 25.21
kg of heroin and 342.81 kg of opium, in September, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Army units, police and the customs also seized three liters of
phensedyl, 37.42 kg of marijuana and 2.11 million tablets of
stimulant drug.
</P>
<P>
During the month, the authorities took action against 366
persons including 313 men and 53 women involved in 251
drug-related cases, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in the first six months of
this year, Myanmar seized a total of 4,927 kg of narcotics
including 219 kg of heroin and 4,471 kg of opium, destroying 15
heroin refineries and over 8,000 hectares of poppy plantations and
taking action against 2,300 people in drug-related cases.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar authorities also confiscated nearly 9 million
stimulant drug tablets in the first nine month of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar claimed in a report issued last week by the
Office of Strategic Studies of the Defense Ministry that it has
prevented 45 billion U.S. dollars worth of heroin from reaching
the streets of the United States since 1988 despite U.S. cut in
assistance to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
