<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Bares Opposition Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga said the main opposition United National Party (UNP)
was trying to sabotage the government's effort in the war against
the rebels, the official Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting Wednesday organized by the Sri Lankan
Women's Congress in Moratuwa of the Western Province, she charged
that through a "despicable, conspiratorial" campaign, the UNP had
sought to come to power.
</P>
<P>
She said that the UNP's conduct at this crucial stage of the
ethnic crisis is deplorable and treacherous. She said the UNP had
formed a group to sabotage the government effort in the civil war
in connivance with certain figures in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
When in government, the UNP had not conducted the war properly
but was now advising the government that its war strategy is
wrong, she said.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said the UNP has a duty to support the government
to seek peace at this stage as it is directly responsible for the
escalation of the conflict following the gruesome riots in July
1983.
</P>
<P>
The UNP, if it has any desire to end the war, has only to
support the government to pass the proposed constitutional reforms
in Parliament which are aimed at solving the war, she said. But
they refused to do so, because "their aim is crystal clear. They
want to prolong the war," the president pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
