<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Rejects Ecuador's Initiative on Border Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Peru's president Wednesday
rejected an Ecuadoran initiative on forming a "binational park"
along his country's unmarked border with Ecuador to end their
aging border dispute.
</P>
<P>
President Alberto Fujimori told reporters that Peruvian law
would not allow both countries sharing a single park on an
undefined border but he would not rule out the possibility of "two
parks" along a clearly demarcated border.
</P>
<P>
"Demarcation is what we need," he said after the two presidents
held separate meetings with Argentine President Carlos Menem and
between themselves, apparently trying to reach a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad said here Wednesday that he
was negotiating with his counterpart in good faith and hoped for a
settlement that would allow them to move on to other issues of
mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue building the foundations for a definitive
peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talks between President Fujimori and his Ecuadoran counterpart
Mahuad had given high rise to hopes for a quick agreement to end
the two countries' half-century feud.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso said during the
Ibero-American summit in Portugal last weekend that a final
settlement might be expected soon.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador agreed before their talks in Buenos Aires to
accept any settlement proposed by the four guarantor nations of a
1942 treaty including Argentina, Brazil, Chile and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Peru and Ecuador have fought three wars in 1941, 1981 and 1995,
with the last two over their border dispute, which claimed at
least 35,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
The disputed region along the two countries' 79 kilometer
unmarked border in a mountainous jungle region, is believed to be
potentially rich in petroleum and minerals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
