<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico, Venezuela Lead Oil Sales to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is the second
largest oil supplier to the U.S. in the first eight months of this
year, with 322.6 million barrels of crude worth 3.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mexico closely followed Venezuela - the United State's top OPEC
oil supplier -- which exported 349.2 million barrels worth 3.6
billion dollars in the same period, it was reported here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Canada was the United States' second most important non-OPEC
supplier in that period with 316.8 million barrels worth 3.9
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia ranked second among U.S. suppliers from the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, with 346.9 million
barrels worth 3.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total U.S. oil imports in that period reached 2.7 billion
barrels from OPEC and non-OPEC producers.
</P>
<P>
Non-OPEC countries like Mexico, Canada, Angola and China among
others sold the U.S. 1.1 billion barrels of crude, 52.2 percent of
the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
