<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges Continued Pressure on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Wednesday in Skopje that Britain would play its part in
maintaining international pressure on Yugoslavia to ensure that
Belgrade keep its promises on Kosovo, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov, Prime
Minister Branko Crvenkovski and Foreign Minister Blagoj Handziski,
Cook said the international community would not make any
concession to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
He said the Milosevic-Holbrooke agreement did not mark the end
of problems but only the beginning of the international
community's efforts to build a stable and peaceful Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"President Milosevic should not make the mistake of imagining
that the international community is going to go away and forget
about his commitment," Cook noted.
</P>
<P>
"We will be watching very carefully to make sure that he sticks
to the agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary also called for a speedy
deployment of the 2000 monitoring personnel in Kosovo to verify
the withdrawal of the Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
Cook thanked Macedonia for permitting the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) to deploy on its soil unarmed aircraft and
pilotless spy planes to watch over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said the NATO move represented "another commitment to
Macedonia's territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian leaders expressed support for the international
community's efforts to settle the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Handziski said out of historical reasons, Macedonia was unable
to join in the United Nations' actions aimed at monitoring the
implementation of the UN resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonian foreign minister again ruled out the possibility
of allowing its territory to be used for military actions over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Cook arrived in Skopje Tuesday on a two-day visit following his
trip to Bulgaria. This is the first visit to Macedonia by a
high-ranking British official. Cook is scheduled to leave the
Macedonian capital for Romania Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
