<HEADLINE> Girl Hurt Wins Suit with 1 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A 10-year-old American
girl, whose hand was injured when a baseball bat fragment struck
her during a 1994 game, won her 1 million U.S. dollars suit in
Detroit, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Alyssia Benejam was sitting in a stand when the Texas Rangers'
Jose Canseco's bat smashed and a piece of it flew to her,
piercing her left hand. She was only 6 at the time.
</P>
<P>
The Wayne County Circuit Court jury Tuesday awarded Alyssia
and her parents $1,008,700 for pain and suffering, medical
expenses and lost economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Since the injury, the girl's left middle finger won't grow,
and the ring finger is growing at a 45-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
"I still play the piano and the flute, but it's tough for me
because I can't bend my fingertips," Alyssia said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
