<HEADLINE> Britain to Take Active Part in Monitoring Kosovo Deal: Cook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain will take an active part
in monitoring the implementation of the latest Kosovo peace deal,
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in the Macedonian
capital city of Skoplje on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cook, currently on a visit to Skoplje, said this during a
working lunch with a Kosovar Albanian delegation headed by chief
negotiator Fehmi Agani, Macedonia's Mak-press reported.
</P>
<P>
Britain upholds its position for a peaceful settlement of the
Kosovo issue, Cook said, noting that the agreement between
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic marked the beginning, not the end, of resolving the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain would play a major role in the implementation
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Warning that the international community was closely watching
Milosevic's actions, Cook urged the Yugoslav leader to fulfill his
obligations under the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
According to other reports, the Kosovar Albanian delegates
called for a referendum on the future of Kosovo -- Serbia's
secessionist province where ethnic Albanians account for 90
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
Agani said after the meeting that his delegation asked Britain
to continue its efforts to help resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman for the delegation Etita Tahiri said a referendum
on Kosovo's future would be the most practical and feasible way to
settle the Kosovo conflict, from both the historical and present
points of view. 
</P>
</TEXT>
