<HEADLINE> Brazilian Stock Markets Buoyed by IMF Bailout Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAO PAULO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Stocks in Sao Paulo and Rio
de Janeiro Wednesday closed with nearly 5.5 percent up on news of
an anticipated International Monetary Fund (IMF) bailout package
which buoyed optimism for investment.
</P>
<P>
The Bovespa index shot up 5.40 percent at the close of the Sao
Paulo stock exchange -- the largest in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that investors' confidence had resumed on news
that the government had reached an agreement with the IMF to run a
budget surplus equal to 2.6 percent of the GDP in 1999, the
condition for an IMF 30 billion U.S. dollar bailout package.
</P>
<P>
In Rio, stocks closed up 5.3 percent despite a low trading
volume.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, reportedly the latest victim of the financial crisis
which started last year in Asia, had lost 25 billion dollars in
foreign exchange reserves since August, when Russia's decision to
default on its debts triggered investment crises in many emerging
markets. 
</P>
