<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Postpones Deadline for Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel said Wednesday it has
decided to postpone a deadline for the current Middle East summit
under way in Washington, averting a breakoff of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu previously set the
deadline of 10 p.m. EDT Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Late on Wednesday night, Netanyahu renewed the threat by saying
that Israel will quit the summit at 6:00 a.m. EDT Thursday unless
the Palestinians meet Israel's demands.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and key U.S.
administration officials have been staying in the Wye Plantation,
Maryland, for seven whole days to break the 19-month deadlock in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier statement on Wednesday evening, Israel identified
the two stumbling blocks as the Palestinian Charter, which
contains several anti-Israel provisions, and whether terrorist
suspects would be extradited to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel asked Palestine to convene a session of Palestine
National Council, or the Parliament, whose 700 members live in
exile, to remove anti-Israel provisions in the charter. Palestine
insists it is unnecessary since the provisions were canceled in
1996 and only need the approval of the Executive Committee.
</P>
<P>
Israel further demands that the Palestinians extradite 30
Palestinians accused of killing Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
