<HEADLINE> Indonesian Minister on Rupiah Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Coordinating
Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita
hopes the rupiah exchange rate would not be lower than 5,000
rupiah against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the rupiah exchange rate will not be lower than 5,000
rupiah to the U.S. dollar, because it would make our export
commodities to lose competitiveness," Ginandjar told reporters
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has been advancing significantly during the past
couple of weeks, touching the 7,000 level at one point during the
Wednesday trading session. The rupiah fell back to 7,400 before
closing at 7,150 against the U.S. dollar on Wednesday afternoon,
compared to Tuesday's close at 7,870.
</P>
<P>
The currency was hovering at a range between 10,000 and 11,000
against the U.S. dollar last month.
</P>
<P>
Because other currencies in the region had also depreciated by
between 35 percent and 40 percent during the past year, a very
sharp appreciation in the rupiah would be harmful to the
competitiveness of the country's export products, national
newspapers Thursday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the appreciation of the rupiah against the
greenback was caused by both internal and external factors.
</P>
<P>
The external factor was the development of the U.S. dollar
exchange rate as the result of the lowering of interest rate by
the U.S. central bank.
</P>
<P>
"The internal factors, particularly the various efforts made to
solve the current crisis, were responded to positively by the
international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
The appreciation of the rupiah also reflected increasing
confidence in this nation, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
