<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Economy Not Isolated From Negative Impact, Forecasts Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- External events have clearly a
negative impact on the European economy, according to the Autumn
Economic Forecasts of the services of the European Commission,
which were published here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts said turbulence in Asian markets and the crisis
in Russia have provoked a slowdown in world growth and in
international trade and have led to downward revisions in the
European Union's growth figure for 1999.
</P>
<P>
For 1999, the growth is forecast to be 2.4 percent in the
15-member EU area and 2.6 percent in the euro zone. Both figures
are revised downwards by 0.6 percentage points on the spring
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The most significant downward revisions, at the level of
individual countries, are in Italy, Britain, Denmark and
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts attributed the downward revision to three main
factors. Firstly, the forecasts reflect progressively weaker
external demand for EU exports following a strong year in 1997;
secondly, the decline in the level of the dollar, if maintained,
will erode the competitive position of EU exporters; finally,
recent turbulence on financial market and the high volatility of
stock market risk undermining the confidence of investors.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU's 1998 economic growth rate is now expected to
be 2.9 percent, slightly above its spring forecasts, despite the
effects of events in Asia and more recently in Russia, according
to the latest forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts also gave an overall favorable picture: economic
growth in the EU area is expected to remain strong over the period
1998-2000, driven essentially by internal consumption and
investment. The EU said its growth should pick up again to 2.8
percent in 2000 on a scenario of unchanged policies.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the EU economy is expected to outperform the other
major industrialized economies of the world throughout the
forecast period because of major positive factors including
expected monetary stability, well-controlled inflation and
well-improved employment situation, according to the forecasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
