<HEADLINE> Southern China Island Province Increases Fixed Assets Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The island province of Hainan in
south China has reversed its economic downward trend by increasing
investment in fixed assets, local officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year, fixed assets
investment increased 8.7 percent year on year to 7.56 billion yuan
(about 900 million U.S. dollars), becoming a force in provincial
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that the growth in the fourth quarter will
speed up and this year's investment target of 18 billion yuan will
be reached.
</P>
<P>
The island province, which is also the country's largest
special economic zone, has been carrying out large-scale
construction of infrastructure projects, with total investment
estimated at 55 billion yuan, the officials said, adding that
investment in the once overheated real estate sector is now under
strict government control.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997, the province's fixed assets investment added
up to 96.5 billion yuan, an average annual growth of 27.8 percent
and accounting for 54.8 percent of the province's GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
