<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Galileo Detects Evidence of Water on Jupiter's Moons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists have
detected new evidence of underground oceans on Europa and
Callisto, two moons of Jupiter, thus bringing hopes of finding
life there and other world in the solar system.
</P>
<P>
Writing on Thursday's Nature, a team of scientists from
University of California, the California Institute of Technology
and NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory said they have come to the
conclusion after analyzing data collected by Galileo spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
They said Galileo measured strong disturbances to Jupiter's
magnetic field as the spacecraft flew over Europa and Callisto.
But the moons lack strong magnetic fields of their own that could
exert such a force. So they suggested that Jupiter's magnetism
must be giving rise to secondary fields within some powerful
electrical conductor on each moon, a phenomenon called
electromagnetic induction.
</P>
<P>
The scientists indicated that the strong conductor on the moons
must be huge bodies of salt water or underground oceans. They
would be within about 60 miles (97 kilometers) of the frozen
surface, and kept from icing over by heat within the interior of
the moons. The researchers assume the water as salt as Earth's
oceans, they hence would be about six miles (9.7 kilometers) deep.
</P>
<P>
Heat and water in liquid form are considered fundamental
requirements for life, they said, if we could find such water on
the moons, we may well expect life forms in such water on the
moons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
