<HEADLINE> Ince Charged with Misconduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Midfielder Paul Ince was
charged with misconduct by the English Football Association on
Wednesday for his behavior in an international game against
Sweden last month.
</P>
<P>
Ince was sent off in the 67th minute of that opening European
championship qualifier on September 5, which England lost 2-1,
for his second yellow card.
</P>
<P>
The Liverpool player was subsequently given a three-match ban
by European governing body UEFA for remarks he made to Italian
referee Pierluigi Collina as he walked off.
</P>
<P>
He also reportedly made a V-sign gesture and an F.A. spokesman
said the charges referred specifically to this.
</P>
<P>
Sources explained the long interval between the offense and
the charges by saying that the F.A. had waited until UEFA had
completed their disciplinary procedures before taking action.
</P>
<P>
Ince, who will not be eligible to play again for England in a
competitive match until they entertain Sweden next June, has 14
days to respond the F.A. charges.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, he could be ruled out of England's coming
friendly matches in November and February as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
