<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Deepens Investment System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China is deepening reform of
investment system as part of the effort to transform the role of
the government, according to Li Rongrong, vice-minister in charge
of the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Li told participants in the just-concluded Changsha fair on
foreign economic and technological cooperation in central and
western China that the ongoing reform will alter the existing
practice under which the government is responsible for approving
all investment projects.
</P>
<P>
The new system will allow investors to proceed with projects,
with the exception of large-scale projects, once they register
with the government.
</P>
<P>
The government will also refrain from interfering in the loan
approval procedures of banks, with related institutions enjoying
greater independence in assessing risks and granting loans.
</P>
<P>
The reform measures are designed to reduce the government
interference in microeconomic activities and allow enterprises to
make internal investment decisions, according to the vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
Li also noted that vigorous measures will be adopted to expand
the stock market and to develop additional investment funds in
order to increase direct financing for enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Market regulations will be further strengthened, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
