<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Summit Enters Critical Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel set a ultimatum for
the Middle East summit Wednesday, threatening to walk out of the
talks if Palestine does not meet its key demands while the U.S.
crafted fresh security proposals to try to salvage the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said his delegation
will go home if there was no substantial progress on two key
issues.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said an Israeli
break-off would be "unfortunate" since "there is a sufficient
basis for peace."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and key U.S.
administration officials have been staying in the Wye Plantation,
Maryland, for seven whole days to break the 19-month deadlock in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Wednesday evening, Israel identified the two
stumbling blocks as the Palestinian Charter, which contains
several anti-Israel provisions, and whether terrorist suspects
would be extradited to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel asked Palestine to convene a session of Palestine
National Council, or the Parliament, whose 700 members live in
exile, to remove anti-Israel provisions in the charter. Palestine
insists it is unnecessary since the provisions were canceled in
1996 and only need the approval of the Executive Committee.
</P>
<P>
Israel further demands that Palestinians extradite 30
Palestinians accused of killing Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government has packed its bags, including the
prime minister. Take-off is scheduled for 10 P.M. (0200 GMT),"
said the statement from Netanyahu's office.
</P>
<P>
"The Prime Minister says: 'If there is substantial progress, we
will stay. If not, we will go,'" the statement added.
</P>
<P>
"Without implementation of Palestinian obligations, without a
solution to the issues of extradition of terrorists and amendment
of the (Palestine National) Charter by the Palestine National
Council, there will not be an agreement," it said.
</P>
<P>
"After the meeting, the Americans left to check if the
Palestinians will respond to these demands and change the draft
accordingly," the Israeli statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis said they had already put some of their equipment
on their plane.
</P>
<P>
With the atmosphere souring on the seventh day of the talks,
Israel and the Palestinians exchanged accusations on which side
was responsible for the slow progress in concluding a
land-for-peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Arafat telephoned 49th birthday congratulations to Netanyahu
and urged him to stay on and complete the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, a close adviser to Arafat, said he had delivered
flowers to Netanyahu on Arafat's behalf.
</P>
<P>
Israel accused the Palestinians of failing to respond to their
security demands.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, in turn, accused the Israelis of "political
blackmail" and of introducing new, last-minute demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
