<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Research to Uncover Differences in E-Commerce Adoption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. research companies
Wednesday announced a joint project that will provide an
industry-by-industry analysis of businesses implementation of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
In addition to reporting on the adoption of e-commerce by
businesses worldwide, the study will also include detailed
descriptions and evaluations of e-commerce applications, hardware
and services.
</P>
<P>
The study will be conducted jointly by SRI International, one
of the world's largest research, technology development and
consulting firms, and Collaborative Marketing, a California-based
Internet marketing company.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide e-commerce is currently estimated at about 10 billion
U.S. dollars and is expected to reach 500 billion dollars by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Researchers involved in this joint project said in a news
release that e-commerce studies need to move beyond mere numbers
and focus on how companies can actually put together e-commerce
solutions. E-commerce is no longer a question of if but of how,
and end-users now want to get the answers to the question of how,
they said.
</P>
<P>
To provide broad coverage of industry-specific development
trends and business strategies in e-commerce, the report by the
two companies will include a dozen industries segments including
banking, manufacturing, mortgage, telecommunications, retail, real
estate, insurance, publishing, health care, oil and gas and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
The research firms said that findings about the successes and
failures of visionary industry-specific organizations will help
companies considering e-commerce determine the costs of an
e-commerce implementation and evaluate e-commerce strategies that
are relevant to their situation.
</P>
<P>
An earlier study based on surveys on European business
executives conducted by a global consulting organization, Andersen
Consulting, found that privacy, security and lack of regulatory
framework were key barriers for the growth of e-commerce. But
most executives in Europe believe e-commerce will have a strategic
impact on their businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
