<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Vetoes U.N. Funding Bill Over Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday vetoed a Congress-passed bill to provide nearly one
billion U.S. dollars it owes to the United Nations because of an
unrelated anti-abortion provision.
</P>
<P>
"I've made it clear many times that I will veto such
provisions," Clinton said in a statement, "Congress sent me the
bill to fund our arrears to the United Nations knowing full well I
would do so. So today, I did."
</P>
<P>
In his veto message to Congress, Clinton said that current law
"already prohibits the use of federal funds to pay for abortion
abroad and for lobbying on abortion issues."
</P>
<P>
"This bill would go beyond those limits," he said, by denying
U.S. support to non-governmental organizations that use their own
funds to perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said: "In the past few days, the Congress persisted in
tying our United Nations dues to unrelated and controversial
social provisions which endanger the health of women and deny them
even basic information about family planning, even though studies
show that countries where women have access to strong family
planning actually have fewer abortions."
</P>
<P>
The vetoed legislation would have authorized the payment of 926
million dollars in back dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 1998 bills, the United Nations estimates
Washington owes 1.3 billion dollars in arrears.
</P>
<P>
With the United States faced with possible loss of its General
Assembly voting rights in the coming weeks, the Clinton
administration has made backup plans this month to pay the bare
minimum in dues, from other accounts, to keep that seat intact.
</P>
<P>
It paid the United Nations 50 million dollars earlier Wednesday
which U.N. officials said will help Washington keep its vote in
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Congress included an additional 197 million dollars in separate
legislation for U.N. accounts. That, along with the 50 million
dollars and another already appropriated 100 million dollars,
should save the U.S. vote in the 185-member assembly, U.N.
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
