<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixth ASEAN Summit, a Most Important Diplomatic Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam considers the sixth
summit of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
scheduled for mid-December in Hanoi as a most important diplomatic
event this year, Vietnam news agency Wednesday quoted a senior
diplomatic as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Deputy Foreign Minister Nguyen Tam Chien noted that
this will be the first time Vietnam hosts an ASEAN summit and that
 the Hanoi meeting will be the last summit of the 30-year old
organization before the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
The sixth ASEAN summit will be an opportunity for member
countries, including Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, to strengthen
their solidarity and further enhance intra-regional cooperation,
as well as to regain trust and support from the international
community for Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia once was considered one of the most dynamic
regions for economic development in the world.
</P>
<P>
The deputy foreign minister, who is also general secretary of
the National Committee for ASEAN summit, said the sixth summit is
expected to approve the "Hanoi Declaration" and the "Hanoi Plan of
 Action".
</P>
<P>
The "Hanoi Plan of Action", which will be carried out between
1999-2005, is a step toward implementing the ASEAN vision 2020.
</P>
<P>
The "Hanoi Declaration" will provide assessment on the current
situation of the region, suggest measures to overcome the on-going
 financial-monetary crisis in Asia and affirm ASEAN member
countries' commitment to maintaining political stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has been accelerating its efforts to make comprehensive
 preparations for the summit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
