<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water, Soil Conservation Work Begins in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
has already begun the largest water and soil conservation project
it has ever undertaken at the upper and middle reaches of the
Qiantang River.
</P>
<P>
The project costs 60 million yuan and is expected to control
600 square kilometers of soil-erosion areas in 23 counties and
cities in the province.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled for completion in the year 2004 and is
expected to benefit future generations.
</P>
<P>
Soil erosion areas in the province now exceed 25,000 square
kilometers, accounting for a quarter of the local land
acreage. The province also has more than 533,000 hectares of
cultivated sloping fields and wasteland now suffering from soil
erosion to varying degrees.
</P>
<P>
Serious soil erosion in the Qiantang River Valley is the major
contributing cause of the annual flooding in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
