<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Reserves Improving Environment in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central
China has set up 33 nature reserves on 540,000 hectares of ground
that have contributed to environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
The forests in the reserves are believed to store 9.2 billion
tons of water annually, and protect nearly 100 million tons of
soil from being washed away.
</P>
<P>
Many rare and endangered animal and plant species also live in
the nature reserves. A 1997 study found 1,949 plants in Daoxian
County's nature reserve, 38 of them under state protection.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial Forestry Bureau official, the
province began to build nature reserves in 1957.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
