<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean President Calls For Calm Following Arrests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo Frei
called Wednesday for calm following the arrest of more than 170
people demonstrating over the arrest of General Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at the capital's international airport, Frei told
reporters he would make a statement on Pinochet's arrest after
meeting with cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
Frei was in Portugal attending a summit of Latin American heads
of state when General Pinochet was arrested in London last
Friday. He could be extradited to Spain to face charges of
murder, torture and genocide.
</P>
<P>
Santiago police detained 177 people Tuesday night following
clashes between supporters and opponents of Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Opposition conservative congress members from the Independent
Democratic Union protested Pinochet's arrest in Santiago by
boycotting sessions, while businessmen called for a boycott of
Spanish and British products.
</P>
<P>
Protesting Chilean congressmen held posters saying "Freedom Now
-- No to the Official Kidnapping." Some of the senators included
former high-ranking officers who served during Pinochet's 17-year
rule.
</P>
<P>
Opposition lawmakers gathered an estimated one hundred women
who hurled eggs, sticks and garbage against the Spanish and
British embassies to protest Pinochet's arrest despite efforts by
police to keep them away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
