<HEADLINE> Israel Issues Ultimatum for Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel said Wednesday it
would leave the Middle East summit in the Wye Plantation, Maryland,
on Wednesday evening if the Palestinians do not satisfy their
demands.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government has packed its bags, including the
prime minister. Take off is scheduled for 10 P.M. (0200 GMT),"
said a statement from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
office.
</P>
<P>
"The Prime Minister says: 'If there is substantial progress, we
will stay. If not, we will go.'," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
"Without implementation of Palestinian obligations, without a
solution to the issues of extradition of terrorists and amendment
of the (Palestine National) Charter by the Palestine National
Council, there will not be an agreement," it said.
</P>
<P>
"After the meeting the Americans left to check if the
Palestinians will respond to these demands and change the draft
accordingly," the Israeli statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis said they had already put some of their equipment
on their plane. 
</P>
