<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Confirms Census Bureau Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate confirmed
Kenneth Prewitt as director of the Census Bureau on Wednesday, a
month after lawmakers warned him to expect strong political
pressure over the use of statistical sampling in the nation's 2000
census.
</P>
<P>
Prewitt, head of New York's Social Science Research Council,
has said that the proper use of sampling -- the statistical
estimation of hard-to-find people -- would improve the census'
accuracy and cut costs. The 1990 census missed an estimated four
million people.
</P>
<P>
But at a confirmation hearing last month, senators told Prewitt
that pressure will mount regardless of how the Supreme Court rules
on sampling.
</P>
<P>
Sampling is strongly opposed by Republicans, who say the
Constitution requires every person to be counted.
</P>
<P>
Census results are used to reapportion seats in the House of
Representatives and to determine distribution of federal funds.
Republicans fear sampling would raise population figures in
previously undercounted urban and minority areas that
traditionally support Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary William Daley, whose department includes the
Census Bureau, called Prewitt "one of the country's most
distinguished social scientists and accomplished executives" in a
statement released after his nomination.
</P>
<P>
In August, a three-judge federal panel killed the Census
Bureau's plans to use sampling. The administration has challenged
that decision, and the Supreme Court is likely to hand down a
final ruling by next Spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Ponder Over Kosovo in Few Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The president of the 15-member Security Council for the month
of October, Jeremy Greenstock of United Kingdom, made the
statement at the end of the council's informal consultations on a
draft resolution on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution was jointly prepared by Germany, Italy,
the United States, Japan, Portugal and Sweden following an
agreement between U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke and
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The Holbrooke-Milosevic agreement was reached after marathon
talks to avert NATO's threat of air strikes against Yugoslavia on
the ground of Belgrade's failure to honor relevant U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We are implementing the agreement in good faith," Vladislav
Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United
Nations, told a news conference here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Serb security forces had not carried out "anti-terrorist
activities" for several weeks except in response to direct
attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior Yugoslav diplomat also accused Kosovo Albanian
political and rebel leaders of failing to comply with Security
Council resolutions, which called for an immediate ceasefire and
an early beginning of the political dialogue and the recognition
of Serbia's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who formed a majority of the population in
the Yugoslav province, have been battling with Serbs for
independence. Serbia is the largest of the two republics that
make up Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
