<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence Found for Oceans on Jupiter's Moons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- New observations of Jupiter by
the Galileo spacecraft provide new evidence suggesting there may
be oceans underneath the ice crust of two of the planet's moons.
</P>
<P>
Previous observations from Galileo, which has been orbiting
Jupiter since December 1995, showed that neither Europa or
Callisto, the two moons, have appreciable internal magnetic
fields.
</P>
<P>
But new data picked up by Galileo found that Europa and
Callisto perturb Jupiter's strong magnetic field as they pass
through it, Krishan Khurana and coleagues of the University of
California, Los Angeles, the United States, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The researchers believed that with no magnetic fields of their
own, the explanation must lie in induced magnetic fields in
conducting layers below the two moons' surfaces.
</P>
<P>
"This phenomenon may best be explained by the existence of
subsurface layers of a conductive liquid -- oceans of salty
water," they wrote in the scientific journal Nature.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
