<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Lower on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets drifted
lower Wednesday on profit-taking after Wall Street failed to hold
highs by Tuesday's close and saw a subdued start.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking from Tuesday's surge clipped the wings of London
blue chips, although losses were limited by improved hopes for
lower U.K. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 fell 45 to 5,206, just shy of the 5,203 session
low. Volume topped 1 billion shares traded, while second liners
continued their positive trend, the FTSE 250 added 7 to 4,638.
</P>
<P>
Minutes from the Monetary Policy Committee's October meeting
revealed members were unanimous in voting for a cut, although two
individuals called for a more significant easing than the quarter
of a percentage point which was delivered.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly expect a cut in November and wouldn't rule out a
half a percentage point," said Paribas' Paul Mortimer-Lee.
</P>
<P>
Early omens had been mixed, as a near 3 percent advance by
Tokyo's Nikkei was tempered by the Dow's slide from mid-session
heights Tuesday. The Dow's lackluster showing Wednesday,
meanwhile, only served to knock the Footsie back, to display more
substantial losses Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals are still wobbly but we could now have
approached a turning point," said Jeremy Batstone, equities
strategist at NatWest.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares fell back on profit-taking, too,
after Tuesday's solid advance. The leading Dax index closed down
72 points at 4,523.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks retreated after Tuesday's confident gains. But
Frankfurt dealings were also tainted with an air of uncertainty,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
"Investors are taking a little break at the moment," said a
Frankfurt-based trader.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks fell back as investors took profits on
Tuesday's rally. But a stable to firmer dollar offered some
support.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. currency is still steady, which means most investors
keep on believing in a Bank of France and a Bundesbank rate cut
before the launch of the euro," said Olivier de la Marche, a
trader at Leven brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
Rate-cut hopes had gained momentum amid comments by Jean-Pierre
Gerard, a member of the Bank of France monetary policy council, to
the French daily Le Monde that France and Germany should lower
their interest rates to counter slowing growth in the two
economies.
</P>
<P>
But some traders had said investors were overreacting to
Gerard's comments. Banking stocks suffered from profit-taking
after surging Tuesday on rate-cut hopes and talk of consolidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
