<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia on Question of U.N. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Sanctions should be an
instrument of last resort when all other means had failed,
Malaysia said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 53rd session of the General Assembly on the work
of the Security Council, Malaysian delegate Hasmy Agam said
sanctions should be imposed only if absolutely necessary, and they
should have clear and specific objectives and parameters.
</P>
<P>
Agam said sanctions should also be clearly targeted and have
specified time-frames and appropriate review mechanisms that were
based on a fair and objective evaluation of the effects and
effectiveness of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said sanctions could have enormous negative
effects on innocent and blameless civilians, including women,
children, the aged and the infirm before they achieved their
objective.
</P>
<P>
He said that unless they were perceived as being fair and
effectively carried out through the strong and consistent support
of the international community, sanctions could run the risk of
being challenged, thereby undermining the prestige and the
credibility of the United Nations itself.
</P>
<P>
Agam added that it was extremely important that sanctions were
not perceived as punitive instruments in the hands of one or two
council members who were intent on punishing a particular country
or countries which they did not like. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
