<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Wednesday afternoon held informal consultations on the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council was discussing a draft
resolution on Kosovo jointly hammered out by Germany, the United
States, Japan, Portugal and Sweden, he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came following an agreement between U.S. special
envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
which was reached after marathon talks to avert the NATO threat of
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has demanded Belgrade's full and speedy
compliance with relevant U.N. resolutions, but stopped short of
authorizing NATO's use of military force against a sovereign
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman announced that the prosecutor of the
International Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia, Louise Arbour,
is planning to lead an investigation team into Kosovo on November
5.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts broke out in Serbia's province in February this year.
Since then, ethnic Albanians, who make up some 90 percent of
Kosovo's population of 2 million, have been battling with Serbs
for independence. 
</P>
