<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Split in Lesotho Ruling Party Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Kelebone Maope, the
Deputy Leader of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD),
Wednesday denied rumors that he is planning to break away from
the LCD, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"People are on a band-wagon to discredit our party. Rest
assured, there is no split within the LCD... it's just nonsense,"
Maope was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, SAPA quoted several sources as saying that Maope and
a large number of intellectuals in the LCD were planning to break
away and form a new party, to be called Lesiba la Ntsu (Eagle's
Feather).
</P>
<P>
The sources said LCD leader Pakalitha Mosisili had fallen out
of favor with party members, when he said he would resign and
dissolve parliament should the Langa Commission find fraud in the
May 23 general election.
</P>
<P>
The three-nation commission, headed by South African
Constitutional Court judge Pius Langa, was established to
investigate claims by Lesotho opposition parties that the
election was rigged in favor of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Sources alleged that Maope's plans to break away had their
roots in the rivalry that erupted between him and Mosisili when
former prime minister and LCD founder Ntsu Mokhehle resigned in
late May.
</P>
<P>
A compromise deal was struck, making Mosisili party leader and
Maope his deputy.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said a precedent had been set by Mokhehle's
maneuvering during a protracted leadership battle which took
place when he was leader of the Basutholand Congress Party (BCP),
a party he led to victory in the 1993 democratic election.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister resigned from the BCP last June,
formed the LCD, and transferred governance to his new party
immediately -- a move which plunged Lesotho into a constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The problem in Lesotho is that if intellectuals within a
party don't agree with their leader, it becomes so easy for them
to just remove that person and put their favorite at the helm," a
source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sources claimed that the splinter group, allegedly supported
by Mokhehle's younger brother, Shakhane, had intended to follow
in the footsteps of the former prime minister and form a
government within parliament.
</P>
<P>
But Maope denied all these claims, saying: "I have no such
intentions. Our party... is more united than ever before."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
