<HEADLINE> Lesotho Military Bases to Be Returned Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho military bases
secured by South African and Botswanan forces would be handed
over to Lesotho Defense Force by the end of the month, South
African National Defense Force (SANDF) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SANDF said in a statement in Pretoria that operations to
collect and destroy damaged ammunition started a week ago and
were nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
"It is intended to have the military bases cleared by October
30, and to hand them over to the Lesotho Defense Force again,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers from South Africa and Botswana entered Lesotho almost
a month ago under the auspices of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to quell rising unrest sparked by
alleged irregularities in the May 23 general election.
</P>
<P>
They ran into resistance from rebel Lesotho soldiers that
resulted in fierce clashes at Makonyane and Ratjimoses military
bases outside Maseru, capital of Lesotho. A Makonyane weapons
and ammunition depot was hit and severely damaged during the
fighting. 
</P>
