<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Use Neutron Beams to Treat Brain Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- British scientists are
investigating ways to perfect a treatment for brain cancer using
neutron beams.
</P>
<P>
The new technique, known as boron neutron capture therapy
(BNCT), is far less traumatic than current treatments and with far
fewer side effects.
</P>
<P>
It works by injecting patients non-toxic boron compound that
accumulates in the brain. A beam of low energy neutrons are then
fired at the tumor area where they react with the compound to
produce cancer-killing nuclear particles.
</P>
<P>
The treatment, already under trial in the United States, is now
only available at nuclear reactor sites where the beams can be
safely generated.
</P>
<P>
Now a team of British scientists are working in Birmingham to
set up the world's first non-reactor site for BNCT, where patients
will be treated in radiotherapy clinics.
</P>
<P>
The researchers are also hoping to improve the compounds used
in the process of BNCT to make treatment more effective.
</P>
<P>
The new compounds will allow radiation treatment to be targeted
more directly to the tumor without causing irreparable damage to
the brain.
</P>
<P>
The research is being carried out on malignant gliomas, which
is resistant to many conventional forms of treatment and new
approaches are urgently needed to help boost survival rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0162 </DOCNO>
