<HEADLINE> Amended Laws to Better Protect Taiwan Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese departments plan to
accelerate the introduction of amendments to laws and regulations
in order to strengthen protection for the rights and interests of
Taiwan businesspeople and improve legal services.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the two-day symposium on the theory and
implementation of the Law on Protecting Investment of Taiwan
Businesspeople, which closed today in the city of Kunshan in east
China's Jiangsu Province, agreed that laws and regulations for
protecting Taiwan investment in inland areas must be enhanced to
keep pace with investment growth and expanded reform on the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
More than 160 government officials in charge of Taiwan
investment affairs in 11 coastal provinces and municipalities and
Taiwan businesspeople attended the symposium at the joint
sponsorship of the Ministry of Justice, the Taiwan Affairs Office
under the State Council and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hui, director of the Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao
Department under the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, said the ministry, to which his department belongs,
is drafting regulations to ensure the effective implementation of
the Law on Protecting Investments of Taiwan businesspeople. He
noted that the ministry has solicited extensive opinions from
related departments and local governments since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The draft regulation on the implementation law includes terms
on capital transfers, arbitration procedures, entry and exit
procedures for Taiwan businesspeople and their families members,
the protection of intellectual property rights and various other
related issues, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Tang Xinghua, an official with the Ministry of Justice,
acknowledged that inland lawyers have helped a number of Taiwan
businesspeople avoid business losses over the past few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
