<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Strives to Remove Defective Components </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the world's
largest aircraft-maker, said Wednesday that its engineers had
completed efforts to locate a defective wiring component in some
100 jets on the production line.
</P>
<P>
Boeing spokeswoman Yvonne Leach said about 100 jetliners in
production at Boeing's plants in Everett, Renton and Long Beach,
California, were found to contain the suspect component, known as
Burndy blocks.
</P>
<P>
No planes with suspect parts had been delivered to customers,
she added.
</P>
<P>
A Burndy block is an electrical connector that splices together
wiring, said Wolf Glende, chief engineer for Boeing 777 systems.
</P>
<P>
The problem was detected after some of the 18,000 Burndy blocks
received by the company failed testing in the wiring shop before
being installed, Boeing officials said.
</P>
<P>
Burndy blocks, which came from an approved Boeing supplier
between August and September, are found on Being's new-model 737s,
as well as the 747, 757, 767, 777 airplanes and on MD-90 and MD-11.
</P>
<P>
Leach said that, by Wednesday afternoon, the suspect parts were
removed from five planes in Everett and 12 in Renton. But she
noted it is more difficult to remove the parts in planes that are
closer to completion.
</P>
<P>
Industrial sources say the company faces a possible new
production delay if the wiring problems affect more aircraft
closer to completion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0170 </DOCNO>
