<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robbery, Car Theft on the Rise in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Incidences of armed
robbery and car theft increased in South Africa in the first half
of this year compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of armed robberies per 100,000 people rose from 73.4
to 90, and that of vehicle theft from 110.4 to 117.8, according
to the latest quarterly crime statistics released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,073 vehicle hijackings were reported between
January and June, which represented a 10.6 percent rise on the
same period last year. Most occurred in Gauteng Province, while
KwaZulu-Natal came second.
</P>
<P>
Most hijackings were carried out at weekends, especially on
Friday afternoons and evenings. Most victims were black men.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of the 20 most serious crimes did not change
much in the first six months of this year, the Safety and
Security Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Decreases were recorded in six of the 20 categories, 13
stabilized and one increased.
</P>
<P>
The murder ratio per 100,000 people fell from 26.3 in the
first six months of last year to 25.9 in the same period this
year. Rape dropped from 57.4 to 52.7, and serious assault from
255.7 to 250.3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
