<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Beset With Financial Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Since the beginning of the
year, Mongolia has been afflicted by serious financial
difficulties, which were expected to grow worse.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the Mongolian financial
deficits in the first nine months of the year hit 50.2 billion
Tughriks (58.4 million U.S. dollars), with revenues totaling 151.6
billion Tughriks (about 176.3 million dollars) and expenditures
201.8 billion Tughriks (234.65 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade dropped by 26.7 percent compared with the same
period last year, with deficits amounting to 119.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the annulment of a previous bank merger has led to a
suspension by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank
of the payment of the promised 45 million dollars for 1998, which
was described by the acting Minister of Finance Bat-edrdene
Batbayar as "adding salt in the wounds."
</P>
<P>
Batbayar said Mongolia was still incapable of taking commercial
loans but had to rely on 40-year-long preferential loans provided
by foreign countries with interest rate lower than one percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's annual expenditures were about 500
million dollars, three fifths of which could be self-earned. The
remaining 200 million dollars came from the preferential loans and
grants provided by foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
Mongolian acting Prime Minister Tsakhya Elbegdorij said the
adverse external conditions were largely to be blamed for the
country's current financial predicament.
</P>
<P>
He said the on-going financial crisis in Asia and the deepening
economic and financial crisis in Russia had directly affected the
Mongolian economy.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the financial difficulties have already developed into
a financial crisis. To ease the crisis, the Great Hural
(parliament) has passed a resolution authorizing the issue of 20
billion Tughriks in national debts.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the government departments have stepped up
tax-collection efforts but to little avail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
