<HEADLINE> Pakistan, ILO Sign Agreement on Eliminating Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) and the Pakistan Carpet Manufacturers and
Exporters Association (PCMEA) Thursday inked an agreement aiming
to phase out child labor from the carpet industry, the country's
largest cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by ILO Deputy Director General K.
Tapiola, who is visiting Pakistan this week, and representatives
of the PCMEA here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
"It is the beginning of a long-term commitment of the ILO and
the government and people of Pakistan to work together towards a
total elimination of child labor in the production of carpets in
the country," Tapiola said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also reflects a commitment on the part of the
carpet manufacturers in Pakistan to address child labor "in a
responsible manner, not by removing the children from the
workplace but rather by transferring them from the weaving looms
to the educational centers," he added.
</P>
<P>
A project jointly funded the U.S. Department of Labor and the
PCMEA, will start in December this year under the frame work of
the International Program on the Elimination of Child Labor which
has been active in Pakistan since 1994, according to a press
release issued by ILO.
</P>
<P>
The goal of this project is to eliminate child labor among
children under the age of 14 in the production of carpets in
Pakistan by gradually phasing them out of the workplace and
providing them with educational opportunities and other options.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the project will target at least 8,000 children
working in the carpet industry including some 2,000 of their
younger siblings and their families.
</P>
<P>
The carpet-weaving industry is the largest cottage industry in
Pakistan. In 1996-1997, Pakistan exported about 3 million square
meters of carpet valued at about 7.5 billion rupees ( 150 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the rural areas families have been weaving carpets for
generations. Children, particularly girls, and adults who face a
lack of opportunities for work outside the home often spend long
hours working at the looms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
