<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Increase Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics show
substantial growth in personal savings deposits in the Chinese
capital for the first nine months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Personal savings through the end of September hit 216.4 billion
yuan, up 18.89 billion yuan on beginning year figures and one
billion yuan more than the pervious year's figure, according to
statistics released by the Beijing Branch of the People's Bank of
China, the nation's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Demand deposits accounted for 53.9 percent of the total, up
23.8 percentage points on an annual basis. The proportion of term
deposits fell by 23.8 percentage points to 46.08 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the accelerated growth in personal savings
to the declining interest in stocks sparked by the adverse impact
of financial turmoil sweeping Asia.
</P>
<P>
Recent treasury bond issues also contributed to the resurgence
of personal savings.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that bonds valued at 27.4 billion yuan, or 99.9
percent of planned issues in Beijing, had been sold by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the displacement of workers due to poor corporate
efficiency have cooled optimism about income prospects and more
people have turned to savings accounts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
