<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, October 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Wednesday night withdrew his threat to quit the Middle East peace
summit as the Clinton administration scrambled to keep the talks
going.
</P>
<P>
"Israel wishes to achieve an agreement and hopes there is a
similar desire on the Palestinians' side," Netanyahu said in a
statement after a lengthy meeting with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on security guarantees. U.S. President Bill
Clinton followed the developments from the White House as U.S. and
Israeli officials worked on revising the security provisions that
would be part of any land-for-peace swap. (US-Israel-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Britain will take an active part in monitoring the
implementation of the latest Kosovo peace deal, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook said in the Macedonian capital city of
Skoplje on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cook, currently on a visit to Skoplje, said this during a
working lunch with a Kosovar Albanian delegation headed by chief
negotiator Fehmi Agani, Macedonia's Mak-press reported. Britain
upholds its position for a peaceful settlement of the Kosovo
issue, Cook said, noting that the agreement between U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic marked
the beginning, not the end, of resolving the crisis.
(Macedonia-Britain-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Peru's president Wednesday rejected an
Ecuadoran initiative on forming a "bi-national park" along his
country's unmarked border with Ecuador to end their aging border
dispute.
</P>
<P>
President Alberto Fujimori told reporters that Peruvian law
would not allow both countries sharing a single park on an
undefined border but he would not rule out the possibility of "two
parks" along a clearly demarcated border. "Demarcation is what we
need," Fujimori said after the two presidents held separate
meetings with Argentine President Carlos Menem and between
themselves, apparently trying to reach a peace accord.
(Peru-Ecuador-Border Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- White House lawyers were rebuffed on Wednesday in
their effort to limit a House panel's impeachment inquiry into
President Bill Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky and
charges arising out of it.
</P>
<P>
In the first meeting between the lawyers from the White House
and the Judiciary Committee of the House of Representatives,
Republicans made clear they are not dropping any evidence already
referred to them by prosecutors and are open to receiving
more. "If other matters are referred to us," either by Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr or another source, "we reserve the right to
consider those issues," Paul McNulty, a spokesman for the panel's
Republican majority said after the meeting.
(US-Impeachment-Lawyers) 
</P>
</TEXT>
