<HEADLINE> Soda Manufacturers Criticized for Targeting Schoolchildren </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The battle field of cola
war has expanded to U.S. schools Wednesday, when a consumer group
criticized soda makers of paying for the installation of vending
machines on campuses.
</P>
<P>
According to the Center for Science in the Public Interest
(CSPI), schoolchildren had become a key target for soda makers who
are willing to pay school boards up to 15 dollars a student for
exclusive marketing rights that include vending machines,
corporate logos on athletic scoreboards, free coupons and other
merchandising.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 schools have signed exclusive marketing
agreements with soda companies this year, and the stepped-up pace
of school merchandising worries some teachers, parents and school
administrators, said the organization.
</P>
<P>
The CSPI urged the Clinton administration to study the public
health impact of soft drink, ban it from public schools, put an
end to advertisements that target at school children, and impose
special taxes on sodas to fund health education campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, soda industry executives were quick to accuse the
group of promoting "unfounded consumer alarm", saying that banning
or taxing sodas was not the way to change the diet of Americans.
</P>
<P>
"Soft drinks have never pretended to be anything more than a
nice refreshment product and consumers are smart enough to make
their own choices," said Jim Finkelstein of the National Soft
Drink Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
