<HEADLINE> Taiwan Ranks as Third Largest Overseas Investor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Taiwanese investors have pumped
40.16 billion U.S. dollars into contracted investments in the
Chinese mainland over the past two decades, making the island the
nation's third largest overseas investor.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) said today that Taiwanese business
people have initiated 40,608 projects in the Chinese mainland,
with actual investments standing at 20.86 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The effects of the regional financial crisis led a drop in
Taiwanese investments during the first nine months of the year,
with the volume actually used falling by 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the decline was lower than the average level in terms of
total overseas investments in the same period, the official told a
symposium on the protection of Taiwanese investment which opened
this morning in Kunshan, Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Taiwanese investments are concentrated in coastal provinces
such as Guangdong, Jiangsu, Fujian and Shandong, as well as the
city of Shanghai, said Wan Hui, director of MOFTEC's Department of
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Trends indicate that Taiwanese investments are moving towards
capital-intensive industries such as manufacturing, real estate,
service, construction and agricultural sectors, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The extension of investment terms from 15-20 years to 20-30
years has sparked a steady expansion in volume, Wang added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
