<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Lebanese Lack of Basic Needs: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Over a third of Lebanese is
living without such basic needs as heating, proper education or a
car, the daily Star quoted an official survey as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, carried out by a team of officials from the social
affairs ministry and a U.N. development program, showed that
214,000 households, or 1,095,000 individuals, live in shortage of
basic needs, which make up 35.2 percent of the country's total
population.
</P>
<P>
The study employed a new U.N. method, the "Unsatisfied Basic
Needs," using 11 indicators to measure the level of basic needs
of households and individuals, such as location, education,
housing services, car ownership and the job of household's head.
</P>
<P>
The outcome showed that about 58 percent of the deprived people
live in urban areas, particularly in Beirut and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
And the proportion of poverty is relatively higher among
families headed by women or with more children, and among the
elderly. Near 60 percent of the heads of deprived households
are wage-earners, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
It also said that over 70 percent of those deprived families do
not have their own cars and 13 percent live without heating. But most
deprived households are connected to the public water network and
sewage system, and have their own houses.
</P>
<P>
The study proposed the government formulate policies to raise
wages, create more jobs, lower the prices of commodities and cut
charges of services such as health and education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
