<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Invests 420 Millions Dollars in Ex-Soviet Republics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Direct investment in the former
Soviet republics by South Korea's top five largest conglomerates
amounts to 420 million U.S. dollars, said the Ministry of Finance
and Economy Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five largest chaebols -- Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo, LG and
SK -- have invested 52 million U.S. dollars in Russia, 106 million
dollars in Kazakhstan, 109 million dollars in Uzbekistan and 153
million dollars in Ukraine as of the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo is the largest investor in the region with 379 million
dollars, which accounts for nearly 90 percent of total investment
by the five chaebols, followed by Hyundai with 29 million dollars,
Samsung 7.8 million dollars, LG 3.9 million dollars and SK 255,000
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo, more active in the region than other South Korean
business groups, will suffer a severe setback if Russia's
financial crisis persists. Russia has declared a moratorium on its
external debt, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine and other former Soviet republics in the region depend
on Russia economically. The International Monetary Fund's failure
to rescue the Russian economy will deal a fatal blow to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
