<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Find Evidence of Seas on Jupiter's Moons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists in
California said Thursday that they had detected new evidence of
underground oceans on two of Jupiter's moons, supporting the hopes
of finding life there.
</P>
<P>
A team from the University of California at Los Angeles (UCLA),
the California Institute of Technology and NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory published their findings in the latest issue of the
journal Nature on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The scientists hypothesized the existence of underground seas
from data collected by the Galileo spacecraft which measured
strong disturbances to Jupiter's magnetic field as it zipped past
Europa and Callisto, two of Jupiter's moons.
</P>
<P>
"One could expect life in such oceans," said Krishan Khurana, a
geophysicist at UCLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
