<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rampant Illegal Timber Trade Worries Zambian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
worried over the rampant illegal timber trade since the country
is losing billions of Kwacha in the timber industry through fraud
and illegal dealings between some forestry officers and license
holders.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at a seminar for timber concession license holders
in Lusaka Wednesday, Alfeyo Hambayi, minister of Environment and
Natural Resources, expressed concern at the manner in which
timber is being smuggled out of the country, said Zambia Daily
Mail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hambayi noted there is enough evidence that the discrepancy
between timber production and revenue receipts has led to loss of
government revenue.
</P>
<P>
The state should be able to raise three billion Kwacha (about
1.5 million U.S. Dollars) annually from the sale of timber,
according to the minister, but it fails to reach the target due
to illegal timber exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Commercial license holders are allowed to cut a maximum of 600
trees in a month but in most cases they bribe the forestry
officers, resulting in 3,000 trees being cut, disclosed Hambayi.
</P>
<P>
The most affected areas are Western and Southern provinces
where reserves have been depleted at alarming levels.
</P>
<P>
Hambayi also revealed that his ministry has got information
that a lot of unprocessed timber is being smuggled by foreigners
using helicopters and by road.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government, Hambayi warned, will mete out
stringent measures against any erring individuals or companies to
protect the forest reserves from any further depletion.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to guard trees and other natural resources
to avert possible environmental degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
