<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Gets Cool Response on Greater U.N. Role Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan received a cool response
from the United Nations Thursday when its Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to give
Japan greater responsibilities within the world body.
</P>
<P>
Komura, who made the request while meeting with Annan on the
U.N. reform, sought the greater position to reflect the financial
contribution Japan has made to the international organization,
Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan only responded that he will make further efforts
to bring about the U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the second largest financial contributor to the United
Nations following the United States. Japan and Germany, the third
largest contributor, are seeking U.N. Security Council permanent
seats.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Annan and Komura agreed on the need to
tackle the problem of firearms, with the United Nations playing a
central role.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who was here for the Second Tokyo International
Conference on African Development, will conclude his three-day
visit to Japan later on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
