<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, IMF Loan Talks Underway: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Advisor to Prime Minister on
Finance and Economic Affairs Hafiz Pasha Thursday said that talks
were underway with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World
Bank on a loan program.
</P>
<P>
Pasha stated this while addressing a press conference at the
head office of the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) in Karachi, the
official Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
"Though, the IMF mission has postponed its scheduled visit on
October 21 to Pakistan, negotiations are still on," Pasha said,
adding that the government intends to continue talks with the two
bodies.
</P>
<P>
However, an IMF spokesman has said in Washington that the
resumption of discussions "depends to a great degree on the
satisfactory resolution of the government's conflict with
independent power producers (IPPs) over power tariffs."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Pakistan suspended a power purchase
agreement with British-run Hub Power Co. (Hubco), alleging the
company bribed officials to raise power tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The country earlier suspended contracts with several other IPPs
and issued notices to others over alleged bribes to secure deals.
</P>
<P>
The IMF-Pakistan talks, which began in September, are aimed at
reviving a 1.56-billion-dollar Enhanced Structural Adjustment
Facility (ESAF), which was suspended after Pakistan detonated
nuclear blasts in May.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's foreign exchange reserves were down from 1.43
billion dollars in May to about 600 million dollars this week,
equivalent to just over two weeks worth of imports.
</P>
<P>
The country's external debts stand at 32 billion dollars and it
has reportedly to pay around 1 billion dollars in debt servicing
by December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
