<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Continues Peace Efforts in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Deputy envoy Dame Ann
Hercus met Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides Thursday to continue
the U.N. efforts to revive the Cyprus peace talks within the
bi-communal formula.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting between the U.N. Special
Representative for Cyprus and Clerides.
</P>
<P>
"I have had a meeting with Mr. Clerides this morning, I'll have
a meeting with Mr. (Rauf) Denktash (Turkish Cypriot leader)
tomorrow and I'll have another meeting with Clerides on Friday
next week," Hercus told reporters after the 50-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
But she refused to give more details about their talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway republic
in 1983, which is recognized only by their close ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal formula.
</P>
<P>
But the peace talks broke down last year when Denktash walked
out of the negotiations to protest against a European Union
decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash also raised a proposal in August, calling for the
establishment of a confederation of two equal states in Cyprus,
which met strong opposition from Greek Cypriot-dominated
government and the U.N.
</P>
<P>
The fresh round of U.N. efforts, which began last week, is
"with a goal of reducing tensions and promoting progress toward a
just and lasting settlement," Hercus said.
</P>
<P>
Hercus had discussions with Clerides and Denktash respectively
last Friday and Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
