<HEADLINE> WBC Boss Wants Holyfield-Lewis Fight in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- World Boxing Council
(WBC) president Jose Sulaiman says he will push for the
heavyweight unification title bout between Lennox Lewis and
Evander Holyfield to be staged in South Africa, national
newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman, who arrived in Johannesburg Wednesday for next
week's annual convention of the world sanctioning body, said he
will talk to U.S. promoter Don King about a request by South
African President Nelson Mandela that the fight be hosted in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Englishman Lewis is the WBC champion; American Holyfield holds
the World Boxing Association (WBA) and the International Boxing
Federation(IBF) titles.
</P>
<P>
The fight is scheduled for March after Holyfield was
guaranteed a 20-million-U.S. Dollar purse by King.
</P>
<P>
"I will return to talk to King to find out what can be done,"
Sulaiman said. "I will talk to him strongly and profoundly. I
will try to bring it here... If it's possible to bring
Lewis-Holyfield here, we will."
</P>
<P>
King, the promoter of the long-awaited bout to unify Lewis'
WBC crown and Holyfield's WBA and IBF titles, is the only
promoter to have staged an undisputed heavyweight title match in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
That was the Rumble in the Jungle between Muhammad Ali and
George Foreman in 1974 in the then Zaire, now the Democratic
Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
On hosting the convention in South Africa from October 25-31,
Sulaiman said it was part of the WBC's commitment to bring the
sport to the continent.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Africa is the future of boxing. We want you to
keep them (the boxers), support them, not let them go," he said,
adding that many boxers from Africa were based overseas.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman said the convention would salute President Mandela
and honor former WBC junior lightweight champion Azumah Nelson of
Ghana as the greatest world champion born in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman predicted Mike Tyson, who was given permission to
fight again by the U.S. authorities this week, will become a
world champion again. He described Tyson as a man with "the worst
mental strength I have seen in my life in boxing".
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman said he intends inviting Tyson to the convention "if
I can get in touch with him". But he said it would be difficult
because Tyson has just been given his license and will have to
undergo medical tests.
</P>
<P>
Sulaiman said he hopes this year's amalgamation of the oldest
organizations -- the WBC and the WBA -- will trigger other
organizations joining them, thus whittling down the number of
"world" sanctioning bodies.
</P>
<P>
The WBC and the WBA harmonized their fight rules in May to
pave the way for undisputed title bouts in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
