<HEADLINE> Thailand's GDP to Grow 1 Percent Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok of Thailand Governor
Chatumongol Sonakul said Wednesday at the central bank that he
expects Thailand's gross domestic product to grow 1 percent next
year with inflation rate and interest rates falling by at the end
of this year, the Thai News agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand's gross domestic product is expected to see 1
percent growth in 1999 compared to about 7 percent contraction in
this year projected by economists.
</P>
<P>
He said that inflation will be 8 percent for 1998, lower than
International Monetary Fund estimates of 9.2 percent. He added
that it won't exceed 5 percent in 1999, which would mark a return
to levels common before an economic crisis hit Thailand in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The central bank chief attributed the declining purchasing
power of Thai consumers, and the stability of the country's
currency, the baht, as the reasons for improved inflation figures.
</P>
<P>
The stable baht will also help bring down interest rates at
banks to 12-13 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The baht is at an 11-month high against the dollar, trading at
37.85 to the dollar early Wednesday. 
</P>
