<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Reform on Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's
Procuratorate issued an impeachment regulation today as part of an
effort to eliminate corruption in government bodies and prevent
certain unlawful practices in procuratorial departments.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Beijing, Deputy Procurator
General Zhang Qiong said the impeachment system under revision
covers investigations of government employees involved in bribery,
embezzlement and dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
"The regulation provides checks and balances to ensure
appropriate actions by procuratorial bodies in charge of
corruption investigations," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Investigations of corruption cases, arrest authorizations and
eventual prosecutions were formerly the responsibility of one
procuratorial department. However, the functions have been the
responsibility of separate departments since introduction of the
anti-corruption campaign in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation divides investigation procedures into
several categories which are handled by reporting agencies,
anti-corruption bureaus, disciplinary departments and examination,
prosecution and appeals departments.
</P>
<P>
The regulation requires different departments to reexamine
investigation results.
</P>
<P>
Procuratorates will practice a collective decision-making
system to avoid decisions made by one person, and senior
procuratorates will offer strengthened guidance to departments on
lower levels. said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also stipulates that directors of
anti-corruption bureaus will rotated to other positions or
departments on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that procuratorate departments will improve
efficiency, and welcome public and media supervision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
