<HEADLINE> 500 TB-Infected Buffalo Culled in S. African Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 500 buffalo
infected with tuberculosis have been culled in Kruger National
Park, with poisoned darts, South African Press Association
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The culling was concentrated in the northern, southern, and
central areas of the park, the biggest nature reserve in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
JJ van Altena, one of the culling co-ordinators, was quoted as
saying that the culling had been going on for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
There are about 20,000 buffalo in the park, according park
staff.
</P>
<P>
Kruger National Park authorities have been trying to establish
the level of infection and the spread of TB because lions in the
park eating infected buffalo carcasses were contracting TB.
</P>
<P>
The disease reportedly had spread to cheetah, at least one
leopard, kudu and baboons.
</P>
<P>
About one month ago, 32 of 33 lions in south of the Sabie
River were confirmed as having TB.
</P>
<P>
Johan Krige, deputy director of the Department of Agriculture
said late September that lions in the Kruger National Park were
being ravaged by an incurable and deadly bovine strain of TB
which could kill them all.
</P>
<P>
Lions have no natural resistance to the disease, spread to
them from herds of infected buffalo, a study by academics from
the University of Pretoria's Veterinary Sciences faculty.
</P>
<P>
There are well over 1,000 lions in the park, according to a
park official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
