<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Takes Measures to Protect Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government will
take "appropriate security" measures to ensure strict protection
of all oil installations including pipelines in the country, the
Provisional Ruling Council (PRC) said.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting of the PRC, Nigeria's ruling body, the
General Officer Commanding of Mechanized Division of the Nigerian
Army, Major General Sarki Muktar said Wednesday in Abuja that
"appropriate security will be put in place for the surveillance
of oil installations," press reports here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the responsibility to guard against future
recurrence was not only that of the government but also of the
communities, adding that "they have their roles to play because
of the distance of the pipelines installations".
</P>
<P>
After last Saturday's oil pipeline fire tragedy which killed
more than 700 people, the Nigerian government has decided to
launch a full-scale investigation into the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Dalhatu Bayero, Group Managing Director of the Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation, was quoted by Vanguard newspaper
as saying Wednesday in Abuja that anyone implicated over the
vandalization of the oil pipelines is to be arraigned for
sabotage before the court.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that this is to deter others who might want to
vandalize oil facilities in the country, adding that a panel was
set up at a top management meeting to look into what led to
Saturday's tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The Pipeline and Products Marketing Company (PPMC) gave its
own accounts of the events while conducting newsmen round the
scene Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
James Ogungbemi, PPMC Executive Director in charge of the
company's operation, attributed the incident to vandals who
allegedly removed the pipeline's valve pit with the intention of
siphoning fuel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the team of fire fighters assembled last Saturday
by the Delta State government had withdrawn their fire fighting
equipment Monday after efforts to extinguish the raging inferno
proved abortive.
</P>
<P>
When a team of top officials of the PPMC in charge of the
pipelines visit the fire site Tuesday along with local energy
correspondents, the pillar of fire was still raging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
