<HEADLINE> Gansu Province Expects Bumper Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, October 22 (Xinhua) -- This year's grain output in
northwest China's Gansu Province is expected to hit a record 8.7
million tons, 500,000 tons more than the previous record and 1.04
million tons over last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The average annual net income for farmers will reach a record
1,400 yuan (169 US dollars), according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for the cotton output to hit 40,000 tons, up
22 percent on 1997, with the output for oil-bearing crops expected
to approach 400,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The fruit output is expected to reach 1.8 million tons, up 15
percent on 1997.
</P>
<P>
The meat output through September stood at 330,000 tons up 7.45
percent, with egg output rising by 1.7 percent to 35,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Local sources attribute the anticipated bumper harvest to
timely rainfall, the introduction of advanced agricultural
technology and increased investments.
</P>
<P>
Gansu invested 518 million yuan in agricultural projects during
1998, with the figure accounting for 13.3 percent of total
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
