<HEADLINE> Thailand to Receive Japan's Aid Early Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda said that a big portion of Japanese 30-billion-U.S.
dollar aid package to bail out Asia's economic trouble will be
given early next year, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin, who just returned from Japan where he held talks with
Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa during the weekend, said
Japan will send a team of experts to assess Thailand's requests
for a share of its 30 billion dollar aid plan for crisis-hit Asian
economies.
</P>
<P>
"We have already discussed in detail how money will be spent,"
Tarrin said to reporters Wednesday. But he gave no details of how
much Thailand will receive from the Japanese aid package.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand was hoping for aid aimed at supporting social
safety net projects, injecting liquidity into the Thai financial
sector, and assistance for small and medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese finance minister unveiled the 30 billion dollar
rescue package at a meeting of the Group of Seven industrial
nations in Washington on October 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
