<HEADLINE> S. African, Rwandan Heads to Meet Over Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela is due to have talks with Rwandan Vice President
Paul Kagame in Pretoria Thursday with the two sides focusing on
regional conflicts in the Great Lake region, the President's
office said.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted presidential aide Parks
Mankahlana as saying that the talks would be confidential, and
that no details would be released.
</P>
<P>
The talks are believed to be part of Mandela's renewed effort
to broker peace in the civil war of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), the latest in the long line of failed attempts.
</P>
<P>
Mandela Monday held "confidential discussions" in Pretoria
with his Ugandan counterpart Yoweri Museveni. His office
announced then that other meetings were planned over the next
nine days with a DRC rebel delegation, and Namibian President Sam
Nujoma in addition to talks with Kagame.
</P>
<P>
Kagame's current visit to South Africa follows continued
accusations that Rwanda and Uganda are backing rebel soldiers
fighting to topple DRC President Laurent Kabila. Uganda has
denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
It also coincides with a meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe, of
leaders of the countries which have sent troops to aid Kabila's
government against the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
