<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK No Longer Expensive Destination for Tourists: Tourist Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is no longer an
expensive destination as it had grown into during the boom years,
Lo Yuk Sui, Chairman of the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA)
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The free market practices have enabled Hong Kong to have prices
 down to stimulate demand and help it remain competitive against
devalued currencies and sharply reduced spending power. And this
was reflected in healthier arrivals and occupancy levels in Hong
Kong's hotels in recent months. "I am confident that we are well
set to prosper from the inevitable upturn in our industry," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lo made these comments when presenting the HKTA's 1997/1998
Annual Report at the Association's 40th Annual General Meeting
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lo explained that he was not suggesting that the heavy
price-cut can be sustained indefinitely. "But at least the message
is permeating through our source markets that Hong Kong is no
longer the expensive destination it has grown into during the boom
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lo praised the cooperative partnership among all sectors of the
tourism industry that has grown out of the downturn and thanked
the Special Administrative Region (SAR) government for its support
including tax breaks and recent decision to appoint a Commissioner
for Tourism.
</P>
<P>
But the HKTA chief warned that the future would not be all
roses. "The next year is going to be as tough as the last one,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Although China's mainland offers the best hope for continued
growth, Hong Kong SAR has to emphasize the need to maintain
international image by continuing to attract the top end of the
market and explore the potential of secondary cities in major
market regions as well as new markets as India, Russia and Middle
East countries, Lo continued.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA needs to re-package the product for changing eras, as
well as to upgrade and improve both the product and the standard
and quality of human resources and services. And investment in the
future is also needed, Lo added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
