<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Food Import Reduced by 33 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia managed to reduce
its food import by 32.92 percent during the first half of this
year, Agriculture Minister Sulaiman Daud said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Food imports declined to 1.55 million tons worth 1.65 billion
U.S. dollars in the first half of 1998 from 1.86 million tons
worth 2.46 billion U.S. dollars in the same period 1997, the
minister said when launching a poultry farm project in Batu Gajah,
some 200 kilometers north of here, the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's import of tropical fruits has drastically gone down
by 96 percent, fish down by 33.7 percent, beef by 18.2 percent,
soybean dregs by 18.4 percent, farm feed corn by 15.9 percent,
sugar by 12.4 percent and livestock by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has a target of becoming an international halal
(allowed by Muslim laws) food producer with a market worth 80
billion U.S. dollars a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
