<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Insurance Industry Grows 12 percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong insurance industry
grew by 12.4 percent in 1997 in terms of premium income, compared
with a 5.6 percent increase in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisional statistics released Thursday by
Commissioner of Insurance Alan Wong, the total premium income of
general business (excluding Lloyd's, which is subject to a
different reporting system) and long term business amounted to 52
billion HK dollars (6.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997,
representing about 3.9 percent of Hong Kong gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
General business gained growth in 1997 after a dismal
performance in 1996. Despite the Asian financial crisis which
began in the latter half of 1997, gross premiums grew by 5.3
percent to 19.5 billion HK dollars (2.5 billion U.S. dollars) for
the year.
</P>
<P>
Property damage business remained the largest class, accounting
for 31 percent of the total gross premiums, followed by general
liability business representing 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Net premiums after reinsurance grew at a slightly lower rate of
5 percent to 12.6 billion HK dollars (1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
1997, which is attributable to the mild decrease in the retention
ratio from 65 percent in 1996 to 64.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Notwithstanding the growth in premium income, the general
insurance industry, after enjoying an underwriting profit for four
consecutive years, suffered an underwriting loss of 60 million HK
dollars (7.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Long term business continued to register a double digit growth
rate of 17 percent in 1997," Wong said. The total office premiums
in force increased to 32.5 billion HK dollars (4.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Individual life business remained the major type of long term
business, contributing some 70 percent of total office premiums.
</P>
<P>
However, the regional financial turmoil "has clearly begun to
impact negatively on the insurance industry in 1998," said Wong.
</P>
<P>
For example, gross premiums of general business for the first
half of 1998 amounted to 9.7 billion HK dollars, representing a
slight drop of 1.1 percent against the same period of 1997, while
underwriting result continued to deteriorate with a loss of 200
million HK dollars (25.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
As at September 30,1998, there were 212 authorized insurers
doing business in Hong Kong. As regards insurance intermediaries,
there were 321 insurance brokers and 40,723 insurance agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
