<HEADLINE> S'pore, Australian Navies to Stage Joint Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 600 officers and
men as well as seven ships from the navies of Australia and
Singapore will engage in a routine joint exercise in the waters
off Northern Australia from October 23 to 30, according to a joint
press release Thursday by the defense ministries of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The week-long exercise, codenamed Exercise SINGAROO 98, is the
fourth in the annual SINGAROO series which is held alternately in
Australia and Singapore. It is Australia's turn this year to host
the exercise.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony of Exercise SINGAROO 98 will be jointly
officiated at by Fleet Commander of the Republic of Singapore Navy
Rear Admiral Lui Tuck Yew and Australian Maritime Commander Rear
Admiral Chris Ritchie.
</P>
<P>
During the exercise, the two navies will work together in the
areas of anti-submarine warfare, anti-surface warfare and anti-air
warfare and the air forces of both countries will provide air
support for the exercises.
</P>
<P>
Exercise SINGAROO is one of many exercises designed for the
mutual professional benefits of the two countries' armed forces
which have extensive professional interactions both bilaterally
and under the Five Power Defense Arrangements (FPDA).
</P>
<P>
FPDA groups Britain, Malaysia and New Zealand in addition to
Singapore and Australia  
</P>
</TEXT>
