<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Texas Floods Claim More Lives, Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday declared 20 counties in the state of Texas as disaster
areas, making them eligible for federal aid.
</P>
<P>
State officials have put preliminary damage estimates at about
400 million U.S. dollars. Flooding across central and southern
Texas worsened Wednesday due to continuing rain.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain, as a result of humid air streaming off two
hurricanes in the Pacific Ocean off the west coast of Mexico, has
caused floods in about 60 of the 254 counties in Texas. Governor
George W. Bush Tuesday asked President Clinton to declare 20
counties disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two people have died from the storms since nearly two
feet of rain fell over the weekend. In the Houston area, an
estimated 5,000 homes were flooded, while at least 2,000 people in
Cuero, a city of 7,000 in Dewitt County, were homeless.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of cattle are missing after weekend rains
caused four major rivers in southern and central Texas to flow
over their banks, uprooting fences on flooded ranches and farms.
</P>
<P>
The latest city to fall victim of the flooding, local officials
say, is Wharton, a low-lying town of 10,200 about 50 miles
southwest of Houston where 40 percent of the homes are threatened
by the flooded Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
State officials called the current flooding the worst in 60
years and asked people to evacuate areas near river banks before
it is too late. 
</P>
</TEXT>
