<HEADLINE> U.S. Texas Floods Claim More Lives And Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Wednesday declared 20 counties in the state of Texas as
disaster areas as 21 persons died and thousands were homeless
there in the worst flooding in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
State officials put the preliminary damage estimates at 400
million U.S. dollars. Ranchers said tens of thousands of cattle
were missing after weekend rains caused the break of banks of four
major rivers in southern and central Texas.
</P>
<P>
In the Houston area, about 5,000 houses were flooded while at
least 2,000 people in Cuero, a city of 7,000 in Dewitt County,
were homeless.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rain, resulted from the humid air streaming off two
hurricanes on the Pacific Ocean off the west coast of Mexico,
caused floods in about 60 of the 254 counties in Texas.
</P>
<P>
As the situation worsened Wednesday with more rain falling in
the areas, State officials urged local people to get out of river
banks before it was too late. 
</P>
