<HEADLINE> West African Gas Pipeline Gets A Major Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The proposed West African Gas
Pipeline (WAGP) project got a major boost Wednesday, as Nigeria
and Ghana signed an agreement for the supply of gas to a power
plant in Tema, Ghana.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Chevron Nigeria Limited, in joint
venture with the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation, will be
supplying 40 million cubic feet of natural gas per day from its
Escravos Gas Project to a 220-megawatt power plant in Tema for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Ghanaian capital Accra between
representatives of the Chevron Nigeria Limited and the KMP
consortium that is building the power plant, local press
reported.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that before the WAGP is commissioned, the power
plant will run on light crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Chevron's chairman and managing director George Kirkland said
at the ceremony that with the feasibility study for WAGP underway
and the governments of Nigeria, Ghana, Benin and Togo
co-operating to accelerate the WAGP, his company is confident it
will be supplying Nigerian gas to the region by the end of year
2001 and then for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
George Kappaz, president and chief executive officer of KMP,
said he hoped that this project will do more than alleviate the
energy shortage in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
Richard Matzke, President of the Chevron Overseas Petroleum
Incorporated, said the agreement "is a key to the development of
the West African Gas Pipeline, a major economic development to
provide a low-cost, environmentally preferred fuel supply for the
entire region." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
