<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Japanese Delegation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said today that China and Japan should adhere to the principles
enshrined in the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship in
order to ensure long-term stable ties in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during a meeting with former Japanese
Prime Ministers Hashimoto Ryutaro and Murayama Tomiichi, and
Sakurauchi Yoshio, former speaker of Japanese House of
Representatives. The Japanese delegation is in China to
participate in activities marking the 20th anniversary of the
signing of the aforementioned treaty.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the treaty reconfirmed the principles of the
Sino-Japanese Joint Communique, and laid a solid political
foundation for the development of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
The treaty also reflected the aspiration of people in the
two nations to extend friendly relations from one generation to
another, according to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two countries have enjoyed a long history of
friendship which dates back well over 2,000 years, and added that
the war of aggression launched by Japanese militarists brought
misery to both countries.
</P>
<P>
"Past lessons should serve as guideposts to the future," said
Jiang, adding that "remembering positive experience and negative
lessons in the development of the bilateral relations is the only
way to carry forward the friendly traditions of the two countries
and expect fruitful bilateral ties in the future."
</P>
</TEXT>
