<HEADLINE> Eleven Foreign Airlines Suspend Flights to S.Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Eleven foreign airlines have
suspended flights to South Korea since last December when the
country was gripped by the financial crisis, the Ministry of
Construction and Transportation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Due to the South Korean won's devaluation and a sharp decline
in the number of South Korean passengers, the 11 foreign airlines
suspended their flights operating through Seoul, the ministry
added.
</P>
<P>
Continental Micronesia was the first foreign airline to cancel
its flights starting on December 29, 1997, shortly after South
Korea turned to the International Monetary Fund for a rescue loan
of 58 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
From January to September this year, Air New Zealand, Turkish
Airlines, Qantas Airways, Garuda Indonesia, Ansett Australia,
India Airways, British Airways, Swiss Air, Philippines Airlines
and Vietnam Airlines suspended flights to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Overall outbound traffic was estimated to have decreased by 25
percent so far this year compared to same period last year,
said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
