<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Price Inflation Hits New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's consumer price
inflation continued to slow down in September of 1999, with the key
barometer Composite Consumer Price Index (CPI) up just 2.5 percent
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure was a new record low since the year-on-year rate of
increase in the Composite CPI was computed from October of
1981. The index increased 2.7 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest figures released by the Census and
Statistics Department, a government spokesman said on Thursday,
the further moderation in consumer price inflation was part and
parcel of the adjustment process taking place as the economy
continued to weather the impact of the regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The lower rate of increase was mainly attributed to continued
easing in private housing rentals, while the freezing of railway
fares and tuition fees since the last price revision in September
of 1997 also contributed.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of 1998, the increase in the
Composite CPI averaged 4.1 percent over the same period of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
