<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Prize Donor Values Mainland Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Lee Quo-Wei, a veteran Hong
Kong banker, told Xinhua here Thursday that he had dreamed of
establishing a "Nobel Prize of China" when he first advocated the
establishment of the Ho Leung Ho Lee Foundation five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Foundation was established in Hong Kong in 1994 for
awarding annual prizes to outstanding scientists on the mainland
in recognition of their achievements in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
This year another 63 distinguished mainland scientists gained
laurels at the awarding ceremony held in Beijing Thursday,
increasing the total number of prize winners to 249.
</P>
<P>
"By rewarding talented scientific and technical persons with
outstanding achievements in China, we hope that the Foundation can
play a part in strengthening the development of the country and
provide impetus for its modernization," said Lee Quo-Wei, who, with
three other donors S H Ho, Kau-kui Leung and Ho Tim, each
contributed 100 million HK dollars (12.8 million U.S. dollars) to
the Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The Foundation, named after the surnames of the four donors,
has granted a total 45 million HK dollars (5.8 million U.S.
dollars) over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Lee, now honorary chairman of Hang Seng Bank, said Wednesday
in an interview with Xinhua: "Education, science and technology
are fundamental to the advancement of China. China has so many
outstanding scientists, and we hope the award is a recognition of
their achievements."
</P>
<P>
The Foundation presented two kinds of awards each year. Till
now, a total of 15 world-class scientists on the mainland have
received the Award of Science and Technological Achievement, each
with a prize of one million HK dollars (128,000 U.S. dollars); and
234 won the Award of Science and Technological Progress, with a
prize of 150,000 HK dollars (19,000 U.S. dollars) each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
