<HEADLINE> Campaign to Give Exposure to Outstanding Musicians Across China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China will launch a nationwide
cultural campaign to discover outstanding singers in the urban and
rural areas of 200 Chinese cities in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shuqin, official with the Ministry of Culture, said that
the the one-year campaign, which will cover almost every part of
the country, has invited dozens of famous Chinese singers and
musicians to serve as judges, including Wang Kun, Li Shuangjiang
and Fu Lin.
</P>
<P>
"There are thousands of amateur troupes and singers in the
country's cities, towns and villages," Liu said, adding that they
are playing a positive role in providing local people with
performances of both classic and popular music and songs.
</P>
<P>
Many of them are active on grassroots stages and their
outstanding talent has been warmly received by audiences, Liu
said, but they seldom have the opportunity to perform at national
events because they live in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will provide these singers and musicians a greater
chance to perform on stages nationwide, and attend international
cultural exchanges and art festivals which will help them develop
their talent and introduce Chinese music and songs worldwide, she
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, audios and videos of their singing and
musical performances will be released to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will be sponsored by China Radio International and
the Audio and Video Publishing House.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
