<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Turns Transit Stop for Slave Trade: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- International syndicates
are using South Africa as a transit point for slave trade between
developing countries and Europe, the United States and Canada,
The Star daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a detective from a South African police unit
investigating the trade as saying that migrants from developing
countries were being lured to a number of "transit countries"
including South Africa "with stories of money and jobs,
land-of-milk-and-honey stuff" in the Western world.
</P>
<P>
He said aliens had to pay for air tickets and were then helped
into South Africa, entering either at Johannesburg International
Airport or landing in neighboring countries and "jumping the
fence".
</P>
<P>
Once in South Africa, criminal agents provided the migrants
with accommodation and documentation before they moved on to the
next destination, where they had to pay off their debt.
</P>
<P>
The victims were either forced into prostitution, drug dealing
or other criminal activities or ended up as virtual slave labor
in factories to pay off their debt.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by an inter-agency, including Interpol,
South African Home Affairs Department and police, and the United
States Immigration and Naturalization Service, hundreds of
thousands of illegal migrants are currently being moved by
international smuggling syndicates from their countries of origin
to western Europe and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The human trade syndicates have identified Johannesburg as a
convenient center to obtain fraudulent documentation.
</P>
<P>
They are taking advantage of the fact that South Africa also
has direct flight and shipping routes to most countries in the
developed world.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is regarded as one of the countries in the
developing world whose citizens do not try to enter other
countries illegally in significant numbers, enabling syndicates
to evade suspicion at ports of entry into the destination
countries, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Trading in human cargo earns smugglers billions of U.S.
Dollars in annual profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 More to Be Executed for S. Leone Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Eleven more civilian, including
a 75-year-old woman were Wednesday sentenced to death by a Sierra
Leonean court for their role in the May 1997 Coup, reports from
Freetown said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
So far, 27 civilians and 34 members of the armed forces have
been sentenced to death for treason, murder and other crimes in
connection with the coup that led to the assumption of power by
the Major Johnny Paul Koroma junta which was later toppled by the
West African intervention forces ECOMOG this February.
</P>
<P>
Of the 34 armed forces members, 10 had their death sentences
commuted to life imprisonment, while the rest 24 were executed by
firing squad Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Brigadier Samuel Koroma, chief of staff of the
Koroma junta, and Colonel Adul Karim Sesay, junta
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
According to Judge Bankole Rashid who delivered the sentences,
the 11 convicted civilians will be hanged. They have the right to
appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slump to Continue For Most of South Korea's Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Most of South Korea's industries
will continue to suffer from sluggish domestic demand in the
fourth quarter of this year, said the Chamber of Commerce and
Industry on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a report on business prospects for major industries in the
fourth quarter, the chamber said major industries, except
petrochemicals and shipbuilding, will see lower exports in the
last three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The chamber pointed out that due to the economic slump in
Southeast Asian countries, it will be hard for South Korean
exports to make impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
Production of motor vehicles is expected to decline 29 percent
to two million this year. Domestic car sales will be halved to
750,000 units, while exports will remain at 1.3 million units,
which was last year's level, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry is expected to continue its slump with
production shrinking 10 percent. Domestic sales of electronic
goods will fall 14.5 percent and exports are expected to decline
8.1 percent to 38 billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the export of semiconductor chips will fall 3.2
percent from last year's figure due to a glut in the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ACFTU Official Urges Addition to Trade Union Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An official with the All-China
Federation of Trade Unions (ACFTU) today urged an addition to the
Law of Trade Unions that will punish activities which obstruct
trade union officials in the exercise of their functions and
powers.
</P>
<P>
Jia Zhiming, director of the ACFTU law department, who is
attending the ongoing 13th National Congress of the Chinese Trade
Unions, also suggested adding items to the law to punish those
who obstruct workers' organizations in joining trade
unions and violating trade union property.
</P>
<P>
The law should provide protection for trade union officials
who are treated unfairly by enterprise leaders.
</P>
<P>
If the establishment of trade unions is obstructed in rural or
private enterprises, the managers of these enterprises should be
punished, he said.
</P>
<P>
The law should also ban the illegal use of trade union funds
and the violation of properties in trade unions' sanatoriums,
cultural centers and clubs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the law must be strengthened with a series of
regulations on establishing a trade union conference system,
protecting the rights of trade union delegates, and punishing
violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
The current Trade Union Law was approved by the National
People's Congress and put into effect in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
