<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets South African National Assembly Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of China's National
People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee Li Peng today told
visiting South African National Assembly (SANA) Speaker Frene
Ginwala that China's NPC is ready to further expand exchanges with
SANA to push forward the friendly and cooperative relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala is the first prominent leader of the SANA to visit
China since the two countries established diplomatic relations at
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that China appreciates the fast growth in economic and
trade relations between the two nations following the
establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Exchanges between parliaments of different countries are an
important part of relations among various countries, Li said,
adding that Ginwala's visit will play an active role in pushing
forward bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The chairman pointed out that the Chinese people had supported
the South African people in their struggle for racial equality and
the fight against apartheid over a long period of time,
establishing profound friendship.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that, as a large African country, South Africa
will continue to contribute to regional peace and development," Li
said. "We appreciate South Africa's stand of upholding the 'one
China' policy."
</P>
<P>
Ginwala said that her current visit is a first step toward close
exchanges between the parliaments of the two countries, and that
both nations are consolidating the basis for better
political and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
She also briefed the NPC chairman on South Africa's
domestic affairs, and invited Li Peng to visit South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
