<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coalition Party Criticizes Israeli Delegation's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel's coalition Shas party
leader Aryeh Deri Thursday criticized Israeli delegation's walkout
threat during peace talks in the U.S., saying such a move would
not be helpful to the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Deri voiced his objection to such a behavior of the Israeli
delegation at the Wye Plantation near Washington in his telephone
conversation Thursday morning with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The walkout from the Wye Plantation Mideast peace summit could
only leave a bad impression to the whole world that Israel is not
interested in moving the process forward and Israel must be blamed
for the failure of the summit talks, Deri was quoted as telling
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Wye summit was in crisis Wednesday night as Israeli
negotiators threatened to walk out, accusing the U.S. of going
back on its word and the Palestinians of evasion.
</P>
<P>
Israel delegation blamed the Palestinian side for not meeting
Israel's demand on the so-called security issue and planned to
fly home. But later on it decided to stay at the summit.
</P>
<P>
During the last seven days, the Wye Plantation summit has
reportedly reached agreements on Israel's 13 percent second stage
troop redeployment in the West Bank, the opening of the Gaza
airport and karni industrial part in Palestinian-controlled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The main areas of contention in the talks as of late Wednesday
night were the issues of convening the Palestinian National
Council to abrogate parts of the Palestinian national charter, the
extradition of prisoners, the confiscation of weapons, the third
redeployment, the reduction of the Palestinian security forces,
the crackdown of Islamic terrorists and others, Israeli media
reported from Wye.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deri also asked Netanyahu that how could Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon snub Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in
their first meeting at Wye Plantation, the Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is Israel's foreign minister and he should known the
diplomatic procedures, Deri told Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Sharon refused to shake Arafat's hands at Wye Plantation Monday
night when the two negotiation teams met for dinner, but Arafat
reportedly "stunk out his chest and saluted" Sharon upon hearing
Sharon's introduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expedition Team to Unveil Tibetan Canyon Mystery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A 60-member expedition team composed
of scientists, explorers and journalists will venture into the
Yalu Tsangpo Daxiagu in Tibet--believed by Chinese scientists to
be the world largest canyon--to explore one of the least known
realms on the earth.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Tibet Autonomous Region today held a grand
ceremony in front of the famed Potala Palace to mark the start
of the expedition which begins tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The team plans to hike across the canyon in southeastern
Tibet and reach the top of the canyon in early
November. From there the team will split into three groups with
separate scientific research missions.
</P>
<P>
The Yalu Tsangpo Daxiagu, located on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, is 496 kilometers long and more than 5,000 meters
deep.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are expected to obtain first-hand material on
the natural ecology and resources of the canyon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, U.S. Start Talks on Sharing Military Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the United States
on Thursday began their negotiations over Seoul's share of the
cost in 1999 to maintain 37,000 U.S troops stationed in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. asked South Korea to pay 440 million U.S. dollars next
year, while South Korea tried to scale back its share to the 1994
level of 260 million U.S. dollars because of the current economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. demand is based on a 1995 agreement, under which South
Korea has to increase its share by 10 percent every year starting
with 330 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But South Korea hoped the U.S. would reduce the payment, which
is almost double the 1997 level of 360 million U.S. dollars if
calculated in the devalued South Korean won.
</P>
<P>
Last year South Korea paid 310 million of its previously agreed
399 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen consented earlier this
year to reduce South Korea's share at his visit here.
</P>
<P>
Washington would not seek to benefit from the economic crisis
of a friendly nation, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to agree on a mutually acceptable
amount before the Security Consultative Meeting convenes next
month in Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
