<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Mulls Law on Administrative Appeal, Securities Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A draft law on administrative
appeal which will allow the public to seek reconsideration of
government violations of their interests is to be considered by
China's top legislature next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Also to be submitted for deliberation is the country's long
awaited securities act, first put before lawmakers six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Two officials, at the request of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, briefed the press today on the two draft laws.
</P>
<P>
"The new administrative appeal law will facilitate a highly
efficient interior mechanism of checks and balances within the
government, and help to institute the system of the rule of law
within the government," said Qing Feng of the Legal Affairs
Bureau of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1990 government regulations on administrative
appeal, the new law enlarges the scope of appealable government
violations from the existing personal right and rights to
possession to all the violations by government bodies and its
employees.
</P>
<P>
According to existing rules, victims must seek the government
agencies at a higher level for reconsideration of violations
committed by lower governmental bodies, and sometime they must
travel thousands of miles to reach that department.
</P>
<P>
However, the new law gives victims the right to choose where to
appeal: a higher level governmental body, or government at or
above the county level near the location of the accused
governmental body.
</P>
<P>
To make things easier for the public, the new law allows
victims to raise appeals verbally or in the written form; and if
such an appeal is not rejected with an explanation, it is legally
regarded as accepted.
</P>
<P>
Reconsideration procedures are further clarified and
supervision over agencies of appeal intensified in the new law,
Qing said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the law was drafted with suggestions from
Premier Zhu Rongji, and reflects his ideas on the clarification
of legal consequences for law violations.
</P>
<P>
On another matter, an official with the NPC Standing Committee
explained that the drafting of the securities act has been
prolonged because China's security market is not yet mature and
several key issues including the kinds of securities the law
should cover, management of the securities market, classification of
direct investment and commissioned services, and credits
transactions, all need to be decided.
</P>
<P>
The draft act consists of 214 articles in 12 chapters and covers
issues from stock listings to self-discipline in the security
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981022.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Bone-marrow Treatment Offers hope to Dying Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A new method to transplant bone
marrow from a mismatched donor means that almost anyone who needs
the potentially life-saving procedure can get it, the Globe and
Mail newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Between 20 to 30 percent of patients who received bone-marrow
from mismatched donors in the hospital in Canada's Calgary city
so far remain free of disease, said James Russell, director of the
bone-marrow-transplant program at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, this means we can offer a transplant to virtually
everyone who needs it," Russell said. "We won't feel limited by
the availability of a suitable donor."
</P>
<P>
For people suffering cancers of the blood, particularly
leukemia, transplants are often the only chance. A donor's marrow
usually must match all six of the recipient's immunological
markers on the chromosomes: three inherited from the mother, three
from the father.
</P>
<P>
Siblings generally have a 1-in-4 chance of being a perfect
match. If they aren't, dying patients must turn to other blood
relations, bone-marrow registries or media pleas.
</P>
<P>
Now scientists from Israel and Italy, who first developed the
technology to transplant bone marrow from mismatched donors on
mice in 1989, have shown that the same procedure can work on human
patients. Doctors pioneering the technique in Canada are reaching
similar conclusions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
