<HEADLINE> U.S. Arms Inspector Recalled From Iraq on Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. weapons inspector in the
U.N. Special Commission for disarming Iraq (UNSCOM) has been
recalled by the commission on charges of espionage in Iraq, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nils Carlstrom, director of the U.N. Baghdad Monitoring and
Verification Center, was quoted by INA as saying that the American
inspector, whom he did not mention by name, violates the rules of
UNSCOM as he shot pictures of an Iraqi missile site by his own
camera on October 8.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the history of the U.N. commission
that a U.S. weapons inspector has been ordered to withdraw from
Iraq on charges of conducting espionage activities.
</P>
<P>
Carlstron told reporters that UNSCOM had ordered the American
inspector to leave Iraq four days after his spying operation.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the Iraqi National Monitoring Directorate
Hussan Mohammed Ameen has disclosed that a pilot of a Chilean
national within UNSCOM also tried to shoot pictures of his
helicopter to an Iraqi test field Tuesday, said INA.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Ameen affirmed that such acts of espionage
have been repeated by the U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing some U.N. arms inspectors of spying
on Iraq's important military installations.
</P>
<P>
Ameen said that it was well known that the American inspector
Scott Ritter had frankly admitted through the international TV
channels of spying in the interests of the American and Israeli
intelligence and delivering to them information concerning Iraq's
security and its sensitive sites.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, a former U.S. marine officer during the 1991 Gulf
War, resigned last month from his post as an important U.N.
weapons inspector, complaining that the U.S. and UNSCOM failed
to take a tough stance toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 decide to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM and
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), accusing them of
being dominated by the U.S. and adopting procrastination policy
regarding their disarmament mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
So far, Iraq has not announced its revocation of the August 5
decision, though it is widely expected that Baghdad will resume
cooperation with UNSCOM and IAEA.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. economic sanctions imposed on Iraq since 1990
following its invasion of Kuwait will not be lifted unless
U.N. weapons inspectors verify that it is free of weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
