<HEADLINE> Australia to Unveil Aid Package at APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia would use next
month's Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) leaders' meeting
to announce a package of bilateral assistance for regional
economies hit by global financial chaos, Australian Prime Minister
John Howard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling his second-term blueprint for the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation group, Howard said the Australian government
had engaged a consultant to survey the needs of regional economies
for technical assistance on economic governance, and what was
being done to meet these needs.
</P>
<P>
"There are substantial gaps," he said in a speech at the 10th
International Conference of Banking supervisors in Sydney. "I will
be announcing in Kuala Lumpur a package of bilateral assistance
which will help economies fill those gaps and I will be
encouraging other APEC members in a position to help to do
likewise."
</P>
<P>
He said the effect of financial chaos on the Asia-Pacific
region had been colossal and conceded that Australia would
continue to be hit, but said domestic economic growth was set to
continue.
</P>
<P>
Howard called on the APEC members to reaffirm their trade
liberalization goals at next month's meeting, saying they must
resist the urge to raise barriers for self-protection in bad
economic times.
</P>
<P>
"The worst possible response to the crisis would be to put up
the shutters," he said. "That would result in competition to raise
tariffs and barriers within the region and outside."
</P>
<P>
"We saw the consequences of this sort of policy in the Great
Depression in the 1930s," he said. "Others won't keep their
markets open if we don't."
</P>
<P>
Howard backed United States President Bill Clinton's call for
urgent action to reform the international financial system.
</P>
<P>
"We must focus on what can be done now to ensure that growth
resumes and to avoid a major credit crunch," Howard added.
</P>
<P>
He also appeared to suggest possible changes to institutions
such as the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank,
saying: "The world has changed dramatically since these
institutions were established."  
</P>
</TEXT>
