<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Media tycoon Rupert Murdoch's
News Corp. reined in the Australian share market Thursday ensuring
it only ended marginally higher despite a strong run by four major
stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed the day 2.2 points, or 0.9
percent, higher at 2,545.2.
</P>
<P>
"There's mixed moves in the market if you look at the strength
in (Australia's leading mining company) BHP, National Bank (of
Australia), the Commonwealth Bank (of Australia), Telstra, but it
has all been offset by the downward move in News Corp.," Shaw
Stockbroking dealer Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. ended the day down 62.9 cents, or 6.08 percent, at
9.71 Australian dollars, its preferred shares lost 56.4 cents, or
6.15 percent, at 8.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the stock succumbed to profit-taking after it
jumped sharply on news that its Fox Entertainment Group Inc. could
raise about 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in its initial public offer.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the market remained fairly cautious and "is
probably going to trade on a conservative manner in comparison to
overseas markets as has been the case," Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector received strong investor support Thursday,
boosting the index 59.1 points, or 1.10 percent, to 5,428 points.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank added 48.3 cents to 20.20 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 17 cents to 19.13
Australian dollars, ANZ bank jumped 1.5 cents to 8.95 Australian
dollars while Westpac bank slipped five cents to 9.45 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, BHP stacked on 18.4 cents to 12.99
Australian dollars after rumors that Duke Energy chief executive
Paul Anderson may take up the helm at the diversified miner.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto added 11 cents to 20.42 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slipped 1.2 points to 1,138.8, while the price
of gold bullion in Sydney closed down at 294.25 U.S. dollars an
ounce compared to Wednesday's close of 297.10 U.S. dollars an
ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover ended the day with 295.36 million stocks
traded for 459.79 million Australian dollars (287 million U.S.
dollars), with falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 491 to
479, while 365 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
