<HEADLINE> Clinton Returns to Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Thursday returned to the Wye Plantation, Maryland, where the
Middle East summit is in an impasse, and said the Israelis and
Palestinians need to make tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
"The hardest decisions, now, at last, are on the table. Israel,
the Palestinians, the region and the world have very much at stake
today," Clinton told reporters before boarding a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the parties will seize this opportunity, and not
retreat from the clear moment to capture the momentum of peace and
keep it moving forward," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton rejoined the discussions on Maryland's Eastern shore
after a week of hard bargaining and a threat by Israelis to walk
out of the talks unless they won more Palestinian concessions on
security and other issues.
</P>
<P>
"There's progress to be made. The president is going back out
there to continue pushing hard. I think we're at a decisive moment
to make tough decisions. We're hopeful that the parties can now
make them," said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart before Clinton
left.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
who had packed his bags and ordered his plane on standby, agreed
to stay and work with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
CIA Director George Tenet on a West Bank security proposal that
Israel could accept.
</P>
<P>
The president was accompanied to the conference site by Sandy
Berger, his national security adviser, and other officials.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Wednesday
the president would become an active participant again only if
enough progress was made by the Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators in agreeing to a U.S. text of a land-for-peace deal
which was presented by Albright for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Rubin called the deal "a rolling document" of less than 20
pages, which was undergoing minor revisions and left room for
compromise between the two sides. 
</P>
