<HEADLINE> NBA Season in Jeopardy as Danger Zone Nears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Locked-out NBA players meet
in Las Vegas today with the league six weeks away from the
"danger zone" of canceling the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't have a deal at some point in December, you're in
the danger zone of no season," deputy commissioner Russ Granik
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner David Stern said the league, which already has
canceled the first two weeks of the season, is prepared to cancel
more games if agreement is not reached by next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"By next week, I think the only issue will be, how much of
December should be canceled, along with November, given the lead
time we need," Stern said.
</P>
<P>
The union had no response.
</P>
<P>
The players' meeting, which superstars Michael Jordan and Karl
Malone, among others, will attend, comes on the 112th day of the
lockout with the players having lost two litigation cases and
close to $100 million in salaries.
</P>
<P>
The players will be presented the league's latest proposal and
could discuss decertification, which could end the lockout but
trigger a protracted court suit.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that what would come out of their meeting is a
decision to return to the bargaining table," Stern said. "We
would hope the majority of players would say, 'Enough fighting.
Let's negotiate,'"  
</P>
</TEXT>
