<HEADLINE> Russia Expels Estonian Spy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An Estonian citizen suspected
of being involved in espionage activities was expelled from
Russia, the Russian Foreign Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Estonian, Ville Sonn, was detained for engaging in visual
reconnaissance over military facilities in the Pskov region, the
Itar-Tass news agency quoted the Federal Security Service as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Security Service said that Sonn, a former member of the
Estonian National Independence Party, was in Russia on a mission
to collect military and political information.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency said Sonn confessed that he was
performing a mission on instruction from the general staff of the
Estonian defense forces.
</P>
<P>
Report from the Security Service said, in order to maintain
good-neighborly relations with Estonia, the Russian side decided
not to bring criminal charges against Sonn but to expel him from
the country with no right of re-entry into Russia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Estonian Embassy in Russia, Jana
Vanamolder, said the Estonian government is still investigating
into the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
