<HEADLINE> INTERPOL Conference Opens in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An international police
conference opened here Thursday to discuss a global strategy to
combat crimes and terrorism for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 143 countries and 11 international
organizations are attending the six-day 67th session of the
International Criminal Police Commission (INTERPOL).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the six-day conference,
INTERPOL President Toshimori Karimoto said the participants will
focus on formulating development guidelines for the next century
and discussing ways to enhance cooperation in combating various
forms of crimes, such as money-laundering, organized crimes,
terrorism and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Chamorro Miguel, director of the INTERPOL Secretary General's
cabinet, told reporters that the conference is a "general
reflection (on the part of the organization) of where to go in the
21st century and how to go."
</P>
<P>
The conference will also adopt a new global anti-terrorism
directory and discuss proposals on new technologies in criminal
research and the organization's budget.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being attended by three interior ministers,
11 deputy interior ministers and 33 chairmen of the police
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The organization has been engaged in developing systems to
fight and prevent crimes in its 188 member states since its
establishment 75 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Habib el-Adli, Egyptian interior minister, stressed
Egypt's readiness to cooperate with international organizations in
anti-crime drives, the importance of information exchange and
global cooperation in pursuing terrorists and criminals.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, struck by a wave of attacks by Islamic militants last
year, has launched a comprehensive campaign to fight terrorism and
overhaul security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
