<HEADLINE> Mubarak Briefed About Syrian-Turkish Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa Thursday briefed Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on the latest developments of the Syrian-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa delivered a message to Mubarak from Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The message dealt with the outcome of the recent Syrian-Turkish
talks aimed at defusing the tensions between the two countries,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
After two-day's meetings between Syrian and Turkish officials,
the two neighbors Tuesday signed an agreement, easing their
weeks-long standoff and heading off a possible regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Damascus pledged to shut down Kurdish
rebel camps in its territory and the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
valley in Lebanon. Syria also agreed not to allow Kurdish rebels
to stage cross-border attacks on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Syria and Turkey were running high in the past
weeks after Ankara threatened to resort to military actions to
stop what it said Syria's support for Kurdish rebels fighting for
an independent state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
For fear of a conflict, Egypt exerted intensive efforts to
mediate between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival in Cairo earlier in the day, al-Sharaa expressed
his country's gratitude to Mubarak, the Egyptian government and
people for the efforts to help defuse the crisis, according to the
news agency.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa flew back to Syria after his meeting with Mubarak.
</P>
</TEXT>
