<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 15 Mozambicans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The outbreak of cholera since
early September has infected 493 people, killing at least 15 in
Mozambique, Mozambican Health Minister Aurelio Zilhao disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said here Wednesday that most of the cholera
cases occurred in capital Maputo, its neighboring town of Matola
and some counties in the north part of the central Zambezia
Province.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Noticias newspaper quoted Zilhao as saying that the
prevention and treatment of the epidemic involves not only the
health ministry, but other departments concerning the
environment, water and food.
</P>
<P>
He called upon all layers of the society to act in a bid to
prevent cholera from occurring and spreading.
</P>
<P>
The health minister noted that some 800,000 Mozambicans are at
present carrying cholera virus.
</P>
<P>
If measures are not taken, the epidemic would break out at any
time, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Zilhao urged people to keep personal hygiene, eating clean
food, drinking boiled water and washing hands after going to
stool.
</P>
<P>
Cholera broke out twice in late 1997 and early this year in
most provinces of this southern African country, taking the death
toll of more than 800 people among over 30,000 infected cases.
</P>
<P>
Hot weather and poor hygiene are the major causes for the
outbreak of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
