<HEADLINE> Li Peng says China Can Approach or Reach Year's Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, has
expressed the belief that China will be able to approach or reach
its economic growth target of eight percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The top law-maker said he is satisfactory with the country's
economic situation in the first nine months this year, describing it
as sound on the whole.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Communist Party of China Central Committee Political Bureau, made
the remarks at the 16th meeting of the 9th NPC's Financial and
Economic Committee which was convened on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the last two days, several ministerial officials in charge
of economic and financial issues delivered reports on the
country's economic and financial situation to the committee.
</P>
<P>
Li spoke after hearing the reports. "It is not easy to achieve
such a good result of economic development," he noted, referring
to the increasingly serious impact of the current Asian financial
turmoils on China and the difficulties caused by the severe summer
floods.
</P>
<P>
In a socialist market economy, some goals are mandatory and
more serve as guidance, he explained, stressing that priority
should be given to readjusting the structure, improving the
quality, and enhancing the efficiency, in order to make the
economic growth a "substantial" one.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the reform, development and stability
should be balanced, he noted. 
