<HEADLINE> Tyson Trying to Rid Himself of Don King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson, with new boxing
license secured, is trying to rid himself of an old problem --
Don King.
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, the fighter hunts for a new promoter for his
1999 comeback, but one with severely limited power and
remuneration.
</P>
<P>
With King and Tyson's 10-year relationship asunder, the
ex-heavyweight champion began depositions with the controversial
promoter's lawyers in the figher's $100 million lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
Tyson gave three hours of testimony in New York yesterday.
King sat nearby at a conference table. The fighter alleges King
engaged in a pattern of deceit and fraud.
</P>
<P>
While the 32-year-old former heavyweight champion searches for
a new promoter, his advisers might have located his first
opponent. And the good news is Brian Nielsen of Denmark is no
Peter McNeeley.
</P>
<P>
No deal is finalized, but negotiations are heating up between
Tyson's advisers and Pallen Mogens, promoter for the 1992 Olympic
bronze medalist who has a 44-0 record.
</P>
<P>
Nielsen can fight. The Dane's not a banger, but he is big.
Because of timing, and difficulties with sites and dates, Tyson
won't fight until January. The newest working date is January 16.
If the fight is not in Las Vegas, January 9 is an option.
</P>
<P>
First, Tyson must find a promoter. Whomever he signs with,
Tyson wants a loan of up to $3.5 million, possibly to be used as
part of a down payment to the IRS for his $13 million tax bill.
</P>
<P>
For his comeback bouts, Tyson plans to pay his promoter
$200,000 a fight, which would be considered a bargain.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's new promoter would serve as a "front man" who is paid
a straight fee. Depending upon the agreement, it could be
structured as a one- or two-fight contract, or a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
Promoter Dan Goossen of America Presents, backed by the Fox
network, has emerged as a front-runner. Goossen was conspicuous
at each of Tyson's appearances before the Nevada commission.
</P>
<P>
Magic Johnson, who has a promoter's license in two states, is
viewed as a less likely selection, though he could be an adviser.
</P>
<P>
After Tyson won his license Monday in Las Vegas, he became
annoyed at Johnson's over-reaching statements in a news
conference. Johnson had told the commission he "hoped" he could
serve on Tyson's new West Coast-based team. "It's a role I'd love
to play," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
Later, he told media, "I'll be involved in all the decision.
Promoting is not like brain surgery. I'm going to bring Mike
along slowly."
</P>
<P>
The former basketball star has no boxing experience but knows
people who can steer him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
