<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Scholar Says Don't Take Tibet As Backward Museum (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A Tibetan scholar today refuted
the idea of keeping Tibet primitive and backward, saying this
might satisfy the curiosity of some tourists and adventurers but
will surely hold back the development of the region.
</P>
<P>
"Some people today still think that everything in Tibet should
remain like it was a few hundred years ago and they try to put the
label 'museum of live cultural relics' on Tibet," said Shesrab
Nyima, associate professor of Tibetology at the Central University
for Nationalities.
</P>
<P>
She mentioned that when a group of foreign tourists set foot on
the soil of Lhasa, capital city of the Tibet Autonomous Region,
they couldn't help shouting their wishes to have a look at the
people of the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly against national nihilism since the cultural
traditions of any nationality do not exist in a state of rest, and
they can develop only after absorbing the cream of other
cultures," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1980s when China started its reforms and
opening-up, not as many farmers and herdsmen in Tibet rely on the
natural economy as in the past. They now know more about the
market economy and have a sense of competition.
</P>
<P>
Especially young Tibetans in major cities and towns now enjoy
pop songs and music as they sip traditional buttered tea. This has
become a new fashion in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Shesrab Nyima pointed out that though Tibetan culture is facing
challenges, it still has the great vitality to allow modern
civilization to take root among its traditions, which is expected
to promote national modernization.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has its own characteristics, which are an important part of
China's languages and characteristics, and ancient Tibetans left
huge numbers of documents, some of which are unique in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
