<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Scholar Says Don't Take Tibet As Backward Museum (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some people agree that the living conditions of Tibetans have
been really improved, but on the other hand, they believe that
these improvements have destroyed their traditional life style. A
few have even said that the "unique culture and religion of the
Tibetans has been damaged almost totally".
</P>
<P>
Shesrab Nyima refuted their views by quoting the Constitution
of the People's Republic of China and the Law of Regional Autonomy
of Minority Nationalities that stipulate in clear terms that China
carrys forward and develops outstanding cultural heritages.
</P>
<P>
She gave the example that King Gesser, an ancient Tibetan folk
epic that used to be handed down orally and in manuscripts and
woodcuts, has been put on a state list of social science research
projects, and three million copies of Tibetan editions have been
published nationwide. This provides valuable material for the
study of ancient Tibet.
</P>
<P>
China often sends Tibetan song and dance troupes to
international art festivals. A recent performance given by a
Tibetan children's art troupe won great success during an American
tour.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
