<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Grain Harvest to Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATER, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian grain production
will experience a severe plunge this year due to two heavy snows
in October that covered more than 100,000 hectares of wheat, said
a Mongolian labor union official Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To date, Mongolia has only harvested 163,000 tons of wheat from
166,000 hectares of land, while the country planted a total of
285,000 hectares of wheat this year, the official said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
At most, only 40 percent of the snow-covered wheat can be
gathered in if the weather improves measurably, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has suffered a continuous drop in wheat production. In
1996, wheat production fell to 220,000 tons from 800,000 tons in
the 1980s. But in 1997, it gained a light rally to 240,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, 200,000 tons of grain can meet only half
of Mongolia's annual domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
