<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Members Asked to Sign Non-Violent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security
organizations throughout the territories summoned on Thursday all
members of the Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) to
sign non-violent commitments.
</P>
<P>
Hamas members in various Palestinian districts in Gaza Strip
and the West Bank were summoned by the security authorities to
sign written commitments that they will not involve in acts which
violate the law, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center reported.
</P>
<P>
The report did not say how many Hamas members were summoned,
but the move was apparently aimed at delivering a message to
Israel that the Palestinian side is serious in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Hamas is one of the main Palestinian Islamic groups that oppose
the Oslo Accords. In the past, its members conducted a number of
suicide bombings inside Israel and other violent activities.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the 29-year-old Hamas member Salem Sarsour from the
West Bank city of Hebron threw two hand grenades at the central
bus station in Israel's southern city of Beersheba, injuring 64
people.
</P>
<P>
Security cooperation is one of the key issues hindering the
progress of the current Israeli-Palestinian summit at the Wye
Plantation outside Washington, the U.S., which began a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Israel insisted that the Palestinians should fight against
terrorists and crack down on Islamic groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
