<HEADLINE> EU Backs French Asbestos Ban in Face of WTO Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 22 (xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
Tuesday announced its rejection of Canadian claims that the French
measure concerning an asbestos ban violates international trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The French measure bans the production, transformation, sale,
importation and marketing of asbestos and asbestos-containing
products, with certain exceptions for applications for which safer
substitutes do not yet exist, an EU news release said.
</P>
<P>
The EU said it is confident that the French measure is
compatible with WTO obligations.
</P>
<P>
Canada on Wednesday requested the establishment of a World
Trade Organization (WTO) panel against the French ban on asbestos
and asbestos-containing products.
</P>
<P>
As is allowed under WTO rules, the EU rejected the request for
the first time. If Canada repeats its request at the next WTO
Disputes Settlement Body meeting, a panel will be automatically
established.
</P>
<P>
According to the EU announcement, Canada claims the French
measure has violated the Agreement on Sanitary and Phyto-sanitary
Measures, the Agreement on Technical Barriers to Trade, and
Articles XI and III of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
It has been scientifically proven that asbestos fibers are
carcinogenic. In France alone about 2,000 persons die of cancer
caused by asbestos every year. The figure for the EU is in the
tens of thousands, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
