<HEADLINE> UK Plutonium "May be in US Warheads", say Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 22 (Xinhua) - The possibility that plutonium
produced by Britain end up in at least 300 US military warheads is
raised by British scientists.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that Britain and America broke the spirit of the
nuclear non-proliferation treaty by diverting nuclear material
from civil nuclear programs for military use.
</P>
<P>
British paper, the Daily Telegraph, quoted Prof Keith Barnham
of Imperial College and his colleagues as saying that according to
the official figures, "There is a 1.4-ton discrepancy in the
amount of plutonium transferred from Britain's civil reactors,
supposedly for civil use in America, under a 1958 agreement."
</P>
<P>
He points out in the journal Nature that, despite claims of
openness by the Department of Trade and Industry, official UK
figures now contain less information than previously.
</P>
<P>
It suggests that there has been an attempt to rewrite history,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
The paper said, the Government changed its line from saying
civil plutonium had never been exported for weapons in 1986 to
saying that it had not happened since 1979 - after the exchanges
ended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
